\fs32 \cf2 Traced ratings origin to Google Places API data\
\
The ratings you see on the map cards are pulled directly from Google Places API \'97 they're Google's aggregated star ratings from public user reviews, not anything generated by LocalBite.\
For example, the data returned for Bar Dos de Mayo shows 4.5
\f1 \'81\'9a
\f0  from 8,905 reviews, and El Rinconcillo shows 4.3
\f1 \'81\'9a
\f0  from 14,023 reviews. Those numbers come straight from Google's database when we look up each restaurant by name and address.\
This raises an important design question for LocalBite, actually. The whole premise of the app is to be different from algorithm-driven aggregators \'97 so there's a real tension in displaying Google ratings prominently. A few options worth considering as you build:\
Don't show Google ratings at all. Lean fully into the editorial angle \'97 the writer's voice is the signal, not crowd-sourced stars. This is the most philosophically consistent choice.\
Show ratings but de-emphasize them. Small, muted text \'97 available if a user wants it, but not the headline. Something like "4.3 on Google" tucked below the writer quote.\
Show only writer count. Instead of stars, show "recommended by 3 writers" \'97 which is a LocalBite-native signal that reinforces your unique value.\
The spec currently doesn't define this, so it's worth a decision before you start building the restaurant card component. What feels right to you?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
