\fs28 \cf6 Architected feasible prototype pipeline leveraging web search and content fetching tools\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Architected feasible prototype pipeline leveraging web search and content fetching tools\
\
Here's an honest breakdown of the pieces involved.\
\
The fetch problem \'97 and its solution\
The biggest blocker for a browser-based prototype is CORS: a widget running in a browser can't directly fetch arbitrary URLs. But there's a clean solution that doesn't require building a backend: Jina.ai's reader API. You call 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 https://r.jina.ai/[any URL]
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  and it returns the page as clean text, with no CORS issues and a generous free tier. This is the single insight that makes a prototype feasible without a server.\
\
The five pieces\
1. Frontend \'97 Modest effort, maybe half a day. A city input field, a Run button, a progress display as the pipeline runs, and the card/filter UI we already have. The Seville widget HTML is mostly reusable.\
2. Anthropic API calls \'97 Straightforward. We already know this works from the widget sessions. Include the 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 web_search
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  tool so Claude can run Phase 1\'963 searches. Manage a multi-turn conversation to step through the phases.\
3. The research prompt \'97 This is the core of the work, probably 2\'963 days of iteration. You need to get Claude to reliably follow the three-phase approach: find publications before restaurants, fetch each article via Jina before extracting anything, and return clean structured JSON at the end. The temptation to short-circuit (assign sources without fetching) is exactly what caused the fabrication problem in our early sessions. Getting a prompt that consistently prevents this takes real testing across multiple cities.\
4. Structured JSON output \'97 Moderate effort, a day. Define the schema (restaurant name, neighbourhood, price, sources array, quote, place ID), instruct the model to return only JSON, handle parsing errors gracefully, and validate the output before rendering.\
5. Google Maps place ID lookup \'97 Modest effort. Either call the Places API from the frontend with a key, or include a step in the pipeline where Claude searches for each restaurant's coordinates. The place IDs in the research summary give you a working reference for how this should look.\
\
Realistic timeline for a working prototype\
A prototype that accepts a city name, runs the three-phase pipeline, and renders verified cards with source attribution: roughly 3\'965 days of focused work. Most of that is prompt engineering and testing, not coding.\
\
The main risks\
The biggest risk is prompt reliability across unfamiliar cities. Seville and Milan worked because we iterated on the process manually. For a city with fewer English-language food writers, or where the top sources are behind paywalls, the pipeline will need graceful degradation \'97 surfacing what it found rather than fabricating what it couldn't.\
The second risk is latency. Running the full pipeline \'97 searches, multiple article fetches, extraction, place ID lookups \'97 could take 30\'9660 seconds per city. The prototype needs a progress display so the user isn't staring at a blank screen.\
\
Where to build it\
Claude Code is the right environment \'97 you'd have the spec file, research summary, and existing widget code all accessible, and you could iterate on the prompt with real cities as test cases. The Anthropic API key is already wired in through the platform.\
Want me to sketch out the prompt architecture or the JSON schema before you start, or would it be more useful to just begin in Claude Code and iterate from there?\
