\cf2 The research prompt is the piece where the most can go wrong, and where the difference between a useful product and a fabrication machine is made. Here's a thorough breakdown.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 What the prompt needs to accomplish\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 At its core, the prompt needs to enforce a strict sequence \'97 find writers, find their articles, read each article, extract only what's explicitly there \'97 and prevent the model from ever jumping ahead. The failure mode we documented across the early Seville sessions is exactly what the prompt needs to make structurally impossible.\
The prompt has to do five things simultaneously:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls52\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Establish the process (the three phases, in order)\
\ls52\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Establish what counts as verified (fully fetched, not snippet-confirmed)\
\ls52\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Define the output schema precisely\
\ls52\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Handle failure gracefully (no source found, article paywalled, page JS-rendered)\
\ls52\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Stay within a token and turn budget that keeps latency acceptable\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 The layers of prompt work\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Layer 1 \'97 The system prompt\
This is the foundation. It needs to define the role (a food research agent that only reports what it has explicitly read), the process (three phases, fetch before extract), the rules (no fabrication, no inference, no plausible-sounding attributions), and the output format (structured JSON, specific schema).\
The risk here is that system prompts get followed loosely, not strictly. A well-written system prompt reduces bad behaviour but doesn't eliminate it. You'll find through testing that certain phrasings are more effective than others, and this is largely empirical \'97 you write it, test it against three or four cities, observe where it breaks, revise. This is iteration you can't skip.\
Layer 2 \'97 Phase-specific instructions\
Each phase needs its own instruction block embedded in the multi-turn conversation, not just the system prompt. Phase 1 should be a discrete step with a clear output (a list of publications and writers, nothing else). Phase 2 should be a discrete step for each publication \'97 search for the article URL, then immediately fetch it before moving on to the next. Phase 3 is the extraction step, operating only on what was fetched in Phase 2.\
The reason to make these discrete turns rather than one big instruction is that it forces intermediate outputs you can inspect and validate. If Phase 1 produces bad results (low-quality publications, no local writers found), you can surface that to the user before wasting time on Phases 2 and 3.\
Layer 3 \'97 The fetch-before-extract constraint\
This is the hardest constraint to enforce reliably. The natural tendency of the model \'97 as we saw clearly in the Seville sessions \'97 is to use search snippets as proxies for article content. It pattern-matches: "this snippet mentions Bodeguita Romero, therefore Bodeguita Romero is in this article." That's the fabrication path.\
The prompt needs to make this explicit: a restaurant does not exist in a source unless the article was fetched and the restaurant's name appeared in the fetched text. Snippet content does not count. Search result titles do not count. The model's prior knowledge does not count.\
This needs to be stated multiple times, in different ways, across the system prompt and the phase instructions. Even then, you should expect it to slip occasionally, particularly for very famous restaurants (El Rinconcillo, for example, is so strongly associated with Seville in training data that the model may "confirm" it without actually checking).\
Layer 4 \'97 The failure handling instructions\
For every fetch, something can go wrong:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls53\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The page is JS-rendered and returns nav chrome but no article content (Gu\'eda Repsol)\
\ls53\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The article is behind a paywall (Azahar Sevilla)\
\ls53\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The URL returned by the search is wrong or dead\
\ls53\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Jina times out or returns garbled content\
\ls53\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The article is in a language the model misreads\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Each of these needs a defined behaviour: log the failure, record the source as unverified, continue to the next source, do not fill the gap by guessing. The prompt needs to make silence preferable to fabrication \'97 if a source can't be verified, it should appear in the output as 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 "status": "fetch_failed"
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  rather than being silently assigned anyway.\
This is a risk vector even with good instructions. The model has a strong prior toward being helpful, which means it tends to try to produce something rather than nothing. In the context of this product, producing something unverified is worse than producing nothing. The prompt needs to repeatedly reinforce that.\
Layer 5 \'97 The JSON schema constraints\
The output schema needs to be tight enough that malformed output is caught before it reaches the UI. Required fields, enum values for 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 lang
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  and 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 pool
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 , a 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 source_status
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  field that distinguishes 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 fetched
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  from 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 snippet_only
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  from 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 fetch_failed
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 , an 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 article_last_fetched
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  date.\
The risk is that the model partially complies \'97 returns mostly-valid JSON with some fields missing or incorrectly typed. The frontend needs to validate before rendering, not trust that the schema was followed exactly.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 The specific risks\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Risk 1 \'97 Famous restaurant inflation\
For any well-known city, certain restaurants are so strongly represented in training data that the model will want to include them regardless of whether they appear in the fetched sources. El Rinconcillo in Seville, Trippa in Milan, Le Comptoir du Relais in Paris. The model knows these are canonical recommendations and will be tempted to include them even if they weren't in a fetched article.\
The mitigation is explicit instruction and output validation \'97 compare the restaurants returned against the source content, flag any that can't be traced to a specific passage. But this is genuinely hard to fully prevent, especially for cities the model knows well.\
Risk 2 \'97 Thin source coverage for unfamiliar cities\
For a city like Palermo or Porto or Thessaloniki, the Phase 1 searches may return very few credible local food writers. The model then faces a choice: either surface low-quality sources (generic travel blogs, TripAdvisor aggregations) or return a small, honest result set. The prompt needs to strongly discourage the first option and make the second feel like a valid outcome.\
The risk is that for thin cities, the prototype looks broken \'97 three restaurants, one source. Technically correct, but not useful. You'll need to decide whether to set a minimum source threshold, expand the search strategy for thin cities, or simply surface the limitation honestly to the user.\
Risk 3 \'97 Source quality drift\
Phase 1 needs to distinguish between genuine local food writing (a Sevillana blogger writing about her favourite bars) and SEO content (a travel site with "Top 10 Tapas in Seville" written by someone who has never been). The prompt can include criteria \'97 named author, evidence of local knowledge, editorial independence, no obvious advertorial content \'97 but the model's judgment on this is imperfect and varies by city.\
You'll find that for well-documented food cities (Paris, Tokyo, New York) the model does well. For less-covered cities it starts accepting lower-quality sources because the pool is smaller.\
Risk 4 \'97 Jina fetch quality variation\
Jina is reliable for simple article pages but struggles with heavily JS-rendered sites, paywalled content, and sites with aggressive bot detection. The prompt can instruct the model to flag poor-quality fetches, but it can't always tell the difference between a genuinely sparse article and a failed fetch that returned partial content. You need a validation step \'97 minimum character count on the fetched text, or a model-assessed "did this fetch succeed" check \'97 before extraction begins.\
Risk 5 \'97 Prompt length vs. latency\
A thorough research prompt with all the necessary constraints, phase instructions, schema definitions, and failure handling will be long \'97 probably 1,500\'962,500 tokens. Combined with the multi-turn conversation and the fetched article content (which can be several thousand tokens per article), you can hit context limits quickly for cities with many sources. You need to design the pipeline to fetch and extract one source at a time, discarding the raw article text after extraction, rather than accumulating everything before extracting.\
Risk 6 \'97 The model second-guessing itself\
In multi-turn pipelines, the model sometimes revisits and revises earlier decisions. It might extract five restaurants from an article in Phase 3, then in a later turn decide that one of them "seems unlikely" and quietly drop it, or add one it remembers from training. Instructions need to explicitly prohibit retroactive modification of extraction results, and the output of each phase should be treated as locked once produced.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 What good prompt testing looks like\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 You need at minimum four test cities:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls54\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
One well-documented EN-heavy city (London, New York) \'97 tests whether the model stays disciplined when it has strong priors\
\ls54\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
One well-documented bilingual city (Barcelona, Lisbon) \'97 tests the dual-language pool logic\
\ls54\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
One moderately-documented city (Porto, Bilbao) \'97 tests source quality decisions\
\ls54\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
One thin city (Palermo, Thessaloniki) \'97 tests graceful degradation\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 For each city you run the full pipeline, inspect the intermediate outputs at each phase, compare the extracted restaurants against the actual fetched article text, and check for any restaurant that can't be traced to a specific passage. You then revise the prompt and repeat.\
Expect three to five full iteration cycles before the prompt is stable across all four test cities. Each cycle involves running the pipeline, auditing the outputs, identifying failure patterns, and revising the specific instructions that caused the failure.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 The core tension\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 The prompt is trying to make a highly capable model behave like a very constrained database query \'97 only return what you explicitly found, never infer, never complete from memory. That runs against the grain of how the model naturally operates. The prompt engineering work is essentially building the right set of guardrails to make the constrained behaviour feel natural and reliable rather than something the model is constantly working around.\
That's why this piece takes longer than it might initially seem, and why testing against real cities with real sources is the only way to know if it's working.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
