\cf2 Interpretation 3 is essentially a research assistant tool \'97 the system proposes, the human decides, the system executes. Here's how I'd build it and what it would actually take.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 How it would work \'97 the user experience\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 The researcher opens the tool, enters a city. The tool runs Phase 1 searches and returns a list of candidate publications and writers \'97 each with the publication name, writer name if identifiable, a brief description of why it looks credible, and the URL. The researcher reviews this list and checks which ones to include. The tool then works through each approved source one at a time: searches for the specific article URL, shows it to the researcher for confirmation, fetches it via Jina, displays a summary of what was found on the page (title, author, approximate length, first few restaurants spotted), and asks for confirmation before extracting. After extraction, it shows the researcher the list of restaurants pulled from that article and allows them to remove any that look wrong. Once all sources are processed, the tool assembles the final JSON pack, the researcher does a final review, and it gets saved.\
The key difference from Interpretation 2 is that the human sees the intermediate outputs and can intervene at every step. The tool is doing the mechanical work \'97 searching, fetching, parsing \'97 but the human is making the judgment calls.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf2 The architecture\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Frontend \'97 a step-by-step wizard UI\
Not a widget but a proper multi-step interface. Five screens:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls57\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
City input and Phase 1 results \'97 candidate publications with approve/reject toggles\
\ls57\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Per-source article confirmation \'97 for each approved source, show the proposed article URL and a fetch preview before committing\
\ls57\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Per-source extraction review \'97 show the extracted restaurant list from each fetched article, allow the researcher to remove entries\
\ls57\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Cross-source assembly \'97 show the full combined list, flag cross-source confirmations, allow final edits\
\ls57\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Export \'97 produce the verified JSON pack and a human-readable summary\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Each screen is a discrete step with a clear action. The researcher can go back to a previous step if something looks wrong.\
Backend pipeline \'97 API calls with Jina fetching\
Each step triggers a specific Anthropic API call with a focused prompt. Phase 1 is one call. Each article fetch and extraction is one call per source. The assembly step is one final call. Keeping the calls discrete means you can inspect each output before proceeding, and a failure in one source doesn't contaminate the others.\
Jina handles the fetching. The API call receives the Jina output and extracts structured data from it. The extraction prompt is simpler and more reliable than the full automation prompt from Interpretation 2, because it's operating on a single confirmed article rather than making source quality judgments at the same time.\
Data model \'97 the city pack JSON schema\
This is worth defining carefully before building anything else, because every other piece depends on it. Based on what we've built across the Seville and Milan sessions, the schema would look something like:\
