\fs36 \cf2 The build sequence\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Week 1 \'97 schema and pipeline skeleton\
Define the JSON schema. Build the Anthropic API call for Phase 1 \'97 city input in, candidate publications out. Build the Jina fetch wrapper. Build the extraction call \'97 article text in, restaurant list out. No UI yet, just the pipeline running in a script you can test from the command line. Test against Seville (you have ground truth to compare against) and one other city.\
This week is the highest-value work. Getting the schema right and the two core API calls working reliably is the foundation everything else sits on. The Phase 1 prompt and the extraction prompt are simpler than the full Interpretation 2 prompt because the human is handling the judgment calls \'97 the model just needs to search well and extract accurately.\
Week 2 \'97 step-by-step UI\
Build the five-screen wizard. This is mostly frontend work \'97 React or plain HTML depending on where you're building. Each screen consumes the output of the previous API call and triggers the next. No novel logic here, just wiring the pipeline to a UI that makes the human's job clear at each step.\
The most important design decision is making the intermediate outputs readable. The researcher needs to be able to quickly assess whether a fetched article looks right \'97 showing the article title, the author name, the first few paragraphs, and the initial list of spotted restaurant names is usually enough.\
Week 3 \'97 testing across cities and prompt refinement\
Run the pipeline against four or five cities, with you or someone else acting as the human reviewer. Observe where the tool produces confusing outputs, where the Phase 1 candidate list is weak, where the extraction misses or fabricates. Revise the prompts. This is the iteration cycle from the prompt analysis \'97 you can't skip it, but doing it with a human in the loop means you catch errors before they reach the output rather than auditing the output afterwards.\
Cities to test: Seville (you have ground truth), Milan (same), Lisbon (bilingual, well-documented), Porto (moderate coverage), somewhere thin.\
Week 4 \'97 export, storage, and the public-facing viewer\
Wire the export to produce the final JSON pack. Add simple storage \'97 even just saving JSON files to a directory is fine for a prototype. Build a read-only viewer (the existing widget HTML, adapted to load from a JSON file rather than having data baked in). At the end of this week you have a complete end-to-end prototype: a researcher uses the tool to produce a city pack, the pack gets saved, the viewer renders it.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

