\fs28 \cf6 Evaluated cloud-hosted and local proxy solutions bypassing CORS restrictions\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Evaluated cloud-hosted and local proxy solutions bypassing CORS restrictions\
\
Yes \'97 a few good ones, depending on how much setup you're willing to do.\
\
The core problem to solve\
The CORS block happens because the browser refuses to call 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 api.anthropic.com
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  directly. The solution in every case is the same: put a small server-side layer between the browser and the Anthropic API. The options differ in where that layer runs and how much work it takes to set up.\
\
Option 1 \'97 Val.town (genuinely browser-only, no installation)\
Val.town is a platform where you write and run server-side JavaScript entirely in a browser-based editor. You write a small HTTP handler that accepts a city name, calls the Anthropic API and Jina, and returns JSON. Val.town runs it on their servers and gives you a public HTTPS URL instantly. The LocalBite widget then calls your Val.town URL instead of Anthropic directly.\
This is the only option that requires zero installation on your machine. You just need a Val.town account (free), and you paste your Anthropic API key into their secret store so it never appears in code. The browser widget stays exactly as built \'97 you just change one URL.\
The tradeoff is that your API key lives in Val.town's infrastructure rather than on your machine, and Val.town's free tier has rate limits that are fine for research use but would need upgrading for anything heavier.\
\
Option 2 \'97 Cloudflare Workers\
Same concept as Val.town \'97 write a small proxy in their browser-based editor, deploy it, get a public URL. Cloudflare's free tier is very generous (100,000 requests per day) and their infrastructure is fast. Slightly more setup than Val.town because you need a Cloudflare account and to navigate their dashboard, but still entirely browser-based with no local installation.\
\
Option 3 \'97 A tiny local proxy script (one command, much simpler than Claude Code)\
If you're willing to open a terminal once, a single Node.js command can run a lightweight proxy on your machine that the browser talks to. No Claude Code, no full script \'97 just:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf6 \cb9 bash\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf10 \cb9 npx localtunnel --port \cf22 3001\cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 paired with a ten-line proxy script. The browser talks to 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 localhost:3001
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 , which forwards to Anthropic. This is technically local but the terminal involvement is minimal \'97 one command to start, one to stop.\
\
Recommendation\
Val.town is the cleanest path if you want to stay entirely in the browser. It's also the most educational \'97 you'd be writing and running the server-side code in a browser IDE, which maps well to how the eventual production app would be structured. The whole setup would take about 20 minutes.\
Want me to write the Val.town handler code and update the widget to point at it?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
