\cf2 That's a very reasonable thing to be uncertain about. Let me give you an honest picture of what's actually involved.\
\
What running from Terminal actually looks like\
For this specific task, Terminal is just a text box where you type commands one at a time and press Enter. You're not writing code, you're not configuring anything complex. The entire setup is about five commands, each of which does one specific thing:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf10 \cb9 1. Check node is installed\
2. Install one package\
3. Set your API key\
4. Run the script\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 That's it. The script then takes over and asks you questions in plain English \'97 approve this source? keep this restaurant? \'97 and you type Y or n and press Enter.\
\
What could go wrong and how bad is it\
The most common issue on a Mac is that Node.js isn't installed. If you type 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 node --version
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  and get an error, you'd need to download and install it from nodejs.org \'97 it's a standard installer, same as installing any other app. Takes about three minutes.\
The second most common issue is the API key. If it's not set correctly the script will tell you immediately with a clear message, and you just run one line to fix it.\
Nothing you do in Terminal for this task can break your Mac or affect anything outside the folder you're working in. The worst case is the script produces an error message and you paste it here and I tell you what to fix.\
\
What Val.town would actually involve by comparison\
Val.town sounds simpler because it's in a browser, but honestly for someone new to this kind of work it introduces its own complexity \'97 you'd need to understand how to write a server endpoint, store secrets in their interface, wire the widget URL to your Val.town deployment, and debug across two separate systems when something goes wrong. The terminal script is a single file that does everything in one place and tells you exactly what it's doing at each step.\
\
My honest recommendation\
If you're willing to try Terminal, I think it's the better choice for this project. Not because it's technically superior, but because it's more transparent \'97 you can see exactly what's happening at each step, the error messages are plain English, and if something goes wrong you can paste the output here and I can help you fix it in seconds.\
The script I wrote is designed with this in mind. Every step prints what it's doing. Approvals are just Y or n. If a source fails to fetch it tells you why and moves on rather than crashing.\
Would it help if I wrote a step-by-step Terminal guide specifically for a Mac with no prior experience? Just the five commands you need, what each one does, and what to do if each one produces an error.\
