\cf2 Great question \'97 the threshold needs to be grounded in something meaningful rather than arbitrary. Here's how I'd think about it.\
\
The signals available and what they actually measure\
Each signal measures something different and they shouldn't be treated as equivalent:\
Number of sources measures independent confirmation. A restaurant named by 3 writers independently is genuinely more trustworthy than one named by 1. This is the strongest signal because it's the hardest to game and the most directly relevant to LocalBite's core promise.\
Language pool measures breadth of perspective. A both-pool entry means writers from different cultural contexts and languages reached the same conclusion independently. This is a quality signal but a binary one \'97 it either is or isn't both-pool.\
Fetch quality measures data reliability. A restaurant extracted from a good fetch (18,000 chars) is more reliable than one from a partial fetch (1,200 chars). This is a trust-in-the-extraction signal rather than a quality-of-restaurant signal.\
Signature dish mentioned measures depth of coverage. If a writer named a specific dish it suggests they actually ate there rather than compiling a list from other sources. A weak but real signal.\
Quote substantiveness measures writer conviction. A quote like "one of Valencia's Michelin-starred restaurants in 2026" (which appeared in the Bonviveur entries) is much weaker than "standing-room-only spot established in 1946 delivering high-impact classic tapas from a husband-and-wife team." The first could have been written without visiting. The second couldn't.\
\
The problem with a single number threshold\
If you add these signals up into a single score you lose information. A restaurant with a score of 6 could be a both-pool entry from a partial fetch with a thin quote, or a single-source entry from a fully fetched article with a rich quote and specific dish. They're very different reliability profiles but the same score.\
A more useful approach is a two-dimensional threshold:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls77\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Confidence in the data \'97 how reliably was this restaurant extracted (fetch quality, quote substantiveness, dish mentioned)\
\ls77\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Confidence in the recommendation \'97 how many independent writers agree (source count, language pool)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 A restaurant needs to pass both dimensions to be auto-approved. Failing either one puts it in the review pile.\
\
What the thresholds should actually be\
Based on what we've seen across the Valencia runs:\
For confidence in the data, the minimum bar should be:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls78\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fetch quality good (over 3,000 chars returned)\
\ls78\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Quote contains at least one specific detail \'97 a dish name, a physical description, a named chef, a price, a year \'97 rather than being a generic summary\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 For confidence in the recommendation, a useful three-tier structure:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls79\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Auto-approve \'97 2 or more sources, or both-pool regardless of source count. These are independently confirmed and go straight into the pack.\
\ls79\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Auto-flag for quick review \'97 1 source, good fetch quality, substantive quote. These are probably fine but you cast an eye over them.\
\ls79\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Auto-reject \'97 1 source, partial fetch, thin quote. The data is too weak to include without human judgment.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 In practice this means both-pool entries and multi-source entries never need human review. Single-source entries from good fetches get a quick scan. Single-source entries from weak fetches get rejected automatically.\
\
The Valencia run as a calibration test\
Looking at the Valencia 2025-2026 pack through this lens:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls80\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The 5 both-pool entries would all have been auto-approved\
\ls80\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The 6 multi-source entries would all have been auto-approved\
\ls80\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The 51 single-source entries would have gone to quick review\
\ls80\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Of those, the 11 you removed were mostly geographic (outside Valencia city) rather than low-confidence \'97 they had good fetch quality and substantive quotes, they were just in the wrong place\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 This reveals something important: the threshold logic catches weak data but doesn't catch geographic errors. You'd still need a separate city boundary rule \'97 which is really Idea 4 (post-run validation) applied specifically to location. The pipeline should know that Alicante and Morella are not Valencia city and reject those automatically.\
\
The practical implication\
The threshold isn't really a single number \'97 it's a small set of explicit rules that together define what auto-approves, what goes to review, and what auto-rejects. Written as rules rather than a score, they're also much easier to explain to Claude Code in a prompt, and easier to adjust city by city if needed.\
Would you like me to draft those rules as a prompt addition to the middle path, combined with the geographic boundary check, and test it on the next city?\
