\cf2 23 minutes is on the longer end but not surprising for what it did. Let me break down where the time went.\
What took the time\
The pipeline ran approximately 15-20 web searches across Phase 1, then fetched 6 URLs through Jina, then made multiple API calls to extract restaurants from each article, then assembled and scored 90 entries. Each of those steps involves a round trip to an external service with its own latency.\
The biggest single time cost was probably the Time Out ES article \'97 63,300 characters is a very large fetch, and extracting 50 restaurants from it requires a substantial API call.\
Is this the rate limit or just the work?\
Both, honestly. On a Claude Pro subscription Claude Code operates under rate limits that throttle how quickly it can make consecutive API calls. When it hits a limit it waits before retrying, which adds invisible pauses you don't see in the output. This is the primary reason it takes longer on an individual Pro account than it would on a Max or Team plan.\
What would make it faster\
A few options in order of impact:\
Upgrading to Claude Max ($100/month) would reduce the rate limit pauses significantly \'97 probably cutting the run time roughly in half for a pipeline like this.\
Reducing the source count from 10-12 to 6-8 would also help \'97 fewer fetches and fewer extraction calls.\
Limiting article size by being more specific in the source URLs \'97 a "best new restaurants 2025" article with 15 entries is much faster to process than a "50 best restaurants" list.\
Is 23 minutes acceptable?\
For a research tool you run once per city, probably yes \'97 you paste the prompt, go make a coffee, come back to review the table. The friction is the permission prompts during execution rather than the clock time. Once those are resolved with option 2 the run is genuinely hands-off.\
If you were running 20 cities in a day it would become a problem. For building a curated library one city at a time it's workable.\
