\cf2 Really good question to be asking \'97 and the honest answer is that Time Out is a borderline source for LocalBite, and there are legitimate reasons to be cautious about it.\
\
The case for including it\
Time Out Barcelona has a named local editorial team, publishes in Spanish and Catalan as well as English, and their 50 best restaurants list is genuinely researched rather than algorithmically generated. The February 2026 date on the previous run was real. They do send writers to eat at restaurants rather than compiling from other sources. For sheer coverage breadth \'97 50 restaurants in a single article \'97 no other source we've found comes close.\
\
The case against\
Time Out is a global media brand, not a local food writer. The Barcelona edition is run by local staff but the editorial framework, incentives, and commercial relationships are set by a London-based parent company. This creates a few specific concerns:\
Advertorial risk \'97 Time Out has a well-documented history of blending paid content with editorial content. Their "Love" badges and sponsored listings sometimes appear alongside genuine editorial picks in ways that aren't always clearly distinguished. A restaurant can pay to be featured in certain Time Out products.\
Tourist orientation \'97 Time Out's primary audience is visitors, not residents. Their best restaurants lists tend to skew toward places that are good for visitors \'97 accessible neighbourhoods, English-friendly service, high name recognition \'97 rather than the neighbourhood spots a local would actually go to. This is the opposite of what LocalBite is trying to surface.\
List inflation \'97 a 50-restaurant list from a single source inevitably includes entries that wouldn't make a more selective 15-restaurant list. In the previous Barcelona run, Time Out's b2 entries dominated the single-source Tier B section, which means a lot of the review burden came from evaluating their lower-confidence picks.\
Global brand vs local voice \'97 the core editorial promise of LocalBite is recommendations from local writers who know the city intimately. Time Out sits awkwardly against that promise \'97 it's local enough to be credible but global enough to raise questions.\
\
What other projects do\
Eater, which has a similar model to LocalBite, treats Time Out as a secondary source \'97 useful for confirming that a restaurant is well-regarded but not sufficient on its own. The New York Times food section and local alternatives like Grub Street carry more editorial weight in their framework.\
\
My recommendation for LocalBite\
Keep Time Out as an eligible source but apply a higher bar to its single-source entries. Specifically:\
