\cf2 You're right that it sounds simple \'97 just filter out 6 entries and write the file. But there are a few reasons it takes longer than expected.\
What Claude Code is actually doing after you hit Enter\
It's not just deleting rows from a list. It's re-reading the full assembled dataset, applying the removals, recalculating all the metadata (confidence tier counts, source counts, both-pool totals, language pool distributions), rebuilding the JSON structure with all nested arrays correctly formatted, and then writing a 78-entry JSON file that could be 15-20KB of structured text. Each of those steps involves a model call, not just a string operation.\
The rate limit factor\
After a long run like this one, Claude Code has consumed a significant portion of its rate limit allowance. The pauses between steps get longer as it approaches the limit, which makes the final export step feel disproportionately slow compared to the work involved.\
What would actually make it faster\
The export step could be much faster if we separated it from Claude Code entirely. Instead of having Claude Code regenerate the JSON, we could have it output just the removal list as a simple array of numbers, and then run a tiny separate script that does the filtering mechanically:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf6 \cb9 javascript\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

