\cf2 Good time to think about this. Here are some additional improvements worth considering for v4:\
\
Pipeline improvements\
Automatic place ID lookup \'97 after the restaurant list is assembled, run a search for each restaurant's Google Maps place ID and add it to the JSON automatically. Right now none of the city packs have place IDs, which means the viewer can't show a map. A post-assembly step that searches for each restaurant by name and city and extracts the place ID would fill this gap without any manual work.\
Price level verification \'97 currently price level is inferred by the model from whatever the article says. A validation step that cross-checks against Google Maps price level data would catch obvious errors \'97 a restaurant listed as \'80 that Google shows as \'80\'80\'80.\
Closure detection \'97 before finalising the pack, run a quick search for each restaurant to check for recent closure news. "Restaurant name Barcelona closed 2025" or "Restaurant name Barcelona cerrado 2025". Flag any that return closure signals for your review. Chifa in the Seville pack is a good example of why this matters.\
Article date verification as a separate step \'97 currently date verification happens during source selection and is sometimes unreliable. A dedicated step that fetches just the article metadata before committing to a source would catch the Devour Tours 2017 problem earlier and more reliably.\
\
Data quality improvements\
Neighbourhood standardisation \'97 currently neighbourhoods are extracted as the writer describes them, which means inconsistent naming. El Born vs Born vs El Born/Sant Pere, Ruzafa vs Russafa, Gothic Quarter vs Barri G\'f2tic. A normalisation map that converts common variants to a canonical form would make filtering more reliable in the viewer.\
Cuisine tagging \'97 extract a cuisine type for each restaurant from the article text. Japanese, Catalan, Mediterranean, Fusion etc. This would enable cuisine filtering in the viewer and is usually mentioned in the articles we're already fetching.\
Opening year \'97 if mentioned in the article, extract the year the restaurant opened. Long-established venues (est. 1940s) are a different kind of recommendation than new openings. The viewer could filter by established vs new.\
Chef name as a separate field \'97 currently chef names appear in quotes and signature dishes but not as a structured field. Extracting chef name separately would enable chef-based filtering and cross-city tracking of notable chefs.\
\
Source quality improvements\
Source freshness score \'97 track how recently each source was published and weight it in the confidence tier. A Jan 2026 article should carry more weight than a Feb 2025 article for a fast-moving restaurant scene.\
Known bad URL list \'97 we now know that Gastronomistas returns 1.6MB pages. A persistent text file in the localbite folder listing known problematic URLs that should always be skipped would prevent rediscovering this problem for every city.\
Source reuse tracking \'97 a file listing which sources have already been used for which cities. If Barcelona Food Experience was used for Barcelona, the pipeline could note this and look harder for fresh sources rather than defaulting to known ones.\
\
Operational improvements\
Estimated run time \'97 at the start of Phase 2, estimate how long the run will take based on the number of sources and average fetch time. Useful for knowing whether to watch it or go make coffee.\
Progress indicator \'97 a simple counter shown after each source completes: "Source 3 of 9 complete \'97 24 restaurants extracted so far." Currently you have no visibility into progress until the review table appears.\
Resume capability \'97 the working.json file we added in v3 is the foundation for this, but a proper resume would also save the source list and fetch status. If the run crashes after fetching 6 of 10 sources, a resume command would skip the already-fetched sources and continue from source 7.\
Cost tracking \'97 log the approximate token usage and estimated cost per run. Useful for understanding the economics of scaling to many cities.\
\
The highest value ones for v4\
Of all of these, parallel fetches (already agreed), automatic place ID lookup, closure detection, neighbourhood standardisation, and cuisine tagging would have the most immediate impact on the quality and usefulness of the city packs. The others are refinements that matter more as the library grows.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
