\cf2 Good question \'97 and the honest answer is that we don't control this directly, it's determined by the web search tool itself.\
When Claude Code runs a web search query, the tool returns the top 10 results from the search engine \'97 similar to the first page of Google results. Claude Code then reads those 10 results and decides which ones are relevant. It does not automatically go to page 2 or 3 of results, and it does not click through to read the full content of each result \'97 it only sees the title, URL, and snippet for each of the 10 results.\
This has a few important implications for LocalBite:\
It biases toward well-known sources \'97 the top 10 results for "best restaurants Barcelona 2025" will consistently surface high-domain-authority sites like Time Out, The Infatuation, and Cond\'e9 Nast. Smaller local bloggers with less SEO authority tend to appear lower in search rankings and may never make the top 10.\
The Jina fetch is what gives us full content \'97 once Claude Code identifies a URL from the search results, fetching it via Jina gives us the complete article text. The search step is just discovery, the fetch step is the actual reading.\
Running more searches helps more than going deeper \'97 since each search only sees 10 results, the way to find more diverse sources is to run more searches with different queries, not to go deeper into any single search. This is why we ask for at least 12 searches in the prompt \'97 each search surfaces a different set of 10 results, giving broader coverage.\
What we could do about it\
A few options worth considering for v4:\
The most effective would be to include a specific instruction to search for smaller local sources explicitly \'97 "search for food bloggers in Barcelona with fewer than 10,000 followers" or "search for restaurant recommendations in Catalan language forums or community sites." These targeted queries are more likely to surface local voices that don't rank in the top 10 of generic searches.\
We could also add a step where after finding the main sources, Claude Code searches specifically within each neighbourhood \'97 "best restaurants Gr\'e0cia Barcelona 2025", "where to eat Poblenou Barcelona 2026" \'97 which tends to surface more local, neighbourhood-specific writers who wouldn't appear in city-wide searches.\
Another option is to ask Claude Code to look at the "people also ask" and "related searches" sections of results and follow those threads, though this is harder to enforce in a prompt.\
The deeper issue is that web search inherently favours established publications over local voices, which is the opposite of what LocalBite is trying to do. This is worth keeping in mind as a structural limitation \'97 the pipeline will always tend to find Time Out before it finds a local Catalan food blogger, regardless of how well the prompt is written.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
