\cf2 Total without pauses: roughly 18-20 minutes. With pauses: 25-35 minutes.\
If we go to 20-25 searches in v4, Phase 1 alone grows to 4-5 minutes. That's meaningful but not the dominant cost.\
The dominant costs are extractions and the export step \'97 and we're already addressing the export with the export utility script.\
\
Speed improvements that cost nothing in quality\
Parallel fetches (already agreed for v4) \'97 fetching all sources simultaneously rather than sequentially saves roughly 2-3 minutes with no quality impact whatsoever. This is the single best speed improvement available.\
Extraction batching within token limits \'97 instead of extracting one source at a time, extract two or three smaller sources together in a single call. The token limit problem came from trying to do all ten at once. Two or three at a time stays well within limits while cutting the number of extraction calls roughly in half.\
Smarter source count \'97 rather than always targeting 10-12 sources, let the diversity gate determine when to stop. If we have 3 EN primary sources, 3 ES primary sources, and 2 CA sources after 15 searches, we don't need to keep searching. Stop early when diversity criteria are met rather than always running to the maximum.\
Shorter article targeting \'97 in the prompt, ask Claude Code to prefer article URLs that look like curated lists (e.g. URLs containing "best", "top", "guide", "mejores", "millors") over general food sections. List articles tend to be shorter and more dense with restaurant names than long-form reviews. Shorter fetches mean faster extractions.\
Skip the working file for small sources \'97 the intermediate working.json write after each source adds overhead. For sources with fewer than 10 restaurants, hold them in memory and only write to the working file every third source or when a source has more than 20 restaurants. This reduces file write operations significantly.\
\
Speed improvements with a small quality tradeoff\
Cap total sources at 8 rather than 10-12 \'97 the marginal value of source 9 and 10 is lower than sources 1-8. The both-pool entries that matter most come from having good EN and ES coverage, not from having the maximum number of sources. Eight well-chosen sources run faster and produce a cleaner pack than twelve sources with two or three low-yield ones padding the count.\
Limit Time Out extraction to 30 entries \'97 Time Out's 50-restaurant list is the single biggest extraction workload in the pipeline. Capping it at 30 entries (the highest-ranked ones) reduces extraction time for that source by 40% while keeping the most relevant recommendations.\
\
The aggregator pre-step \'97 making it fast\
The aggregator fetch idea (Option 5) sounds like it adds time but it doesn't have to. Instead of fetching multiple aggregator pages, fetch just one well-chosen one before Phase 1. A single Jina fetch of a "best food blogs Barcelona" page takes 15 seconds and seeds the candidate pool with local bloggers that all subsequent searches can confirm. Net addition to run time: 15-30 seconds.\
\
The search plan approach \'97 making it fast\
Writing a search plan to a file before running searches sounds like extra overhead but it actually saves time by preventing redundant searches. Without a plan, the model sometimes runs variations of the same query. With a plan covering 20 distinct angles, each search is guaranteed to be different. The plan takes about 30 seconds to write and saves 2-3 redundant searches.\
\
