\cf2 Yes \'97 37 minutes is too long. Looking at what happened in this run, there are a few specific culprits beyond what we've already identified:\
What made this run slow\
The context compaction notice at the top ("Conversation compacted") tells us the session hit a context limit mid-run and had to compress its memory. That pause alone probably cost 5-8 minutes invisibly.\
The one-at-a-time extraction with file writes after each source \'97 which we added to prevent crashes \'97 added overhead we didn't fully account for. Each write-confirm-proceed cycle adds about 30-45 seconds per source. With 10 sources that's 5-7 minutes of pure overhead that didn't exist in earlier runs.\
The Phase 3 assembly from the working.json file, then scoring, then concentration cap calculation, then recommended removals, then table generation all happen sequentially as separate model calls. That chain probably took 10-12 minutes on its own.\
The honest picture for v4\
With all the improvements we're planning \'97 parallel fetches, paired extraction batching, 20-25 searches, aggregator pre-fetch \'97 the run time could go either way. The parallel fetches and batched extractions would save time. The additional searches would add time. The aggregator pre-fetch adds time.\
The real answer is that Claude Code on a Pro account has inherent rate limit pauses that we can't fully control. The 37 minutes includes real work time plus invisible waiting.\
The most impactful speed change for v4 that we haven't discussed yet is moving the export entirely out of Claude Code. If Phase 3 ends with Claude Code writing the raw JSON and nothing else \'97 no scoring, no table generation, no removals \'97 and we do all of that in a separate fast script, the Claude Code portion of the run drops to roughly 15-18 minutes. The review table and removal step happen in a lightweight browser tool or Terminal script that runs instantly.\
