Thorough documentation of sources, methodology, and findings\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 What we don't have yet is anything a user can actually interact with. No website, no viewer, no way for anyone other than you to see or use the research.\
\
The tension worth naming\
We've been iterating on the research pipeline for many sessions and it's genuinely getting better \'97 v4 is meaningfully stronger than v1. But there's a risk of infinite pipeline refinement without ever building the product that the pipeline feeds into.\
The spec at 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 /mnt/user-data/outputs/local-eats-spec.md
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  describes a web product. We have good data for three cities. At some point the question shifts from "how do we research better" to "what are we actually building and for whom."\
\
Three honest questions worth sitting with\
1. Who is the user?\
The original vision was travellers and locals looking for restaurant recommendations from trusted local writers rather than aggregators. Is that still the vision? Because the pipeline we've built skews toward visitors \'97 The Infatuation, Barcelona Food Experience, Fancy Nancista are all written for people who don't live there. The genuinely local Catalan sources (Ara, ElNacional, Beteve) are harder to fetch and harder to present to an English-speaking audience.\
2. What is the competitive advantage?\
The core claim is source transparency \'97 showing users not just a recommendation but who made it, why they're credible, and what they specifically said. That's genuinely differentiated from TripAdvisor and Google Maps. But it only holds up if the sourcing is actually rigorous. The both-pool signal, the primary vs secondary distinction, the fetch-before-extract discipline \'97 these are real quality markers. The question is whether users will care enough to seek them out.\
3. What's the minimum useful product?\
You have three city packs in JSON format sitting in a folder on your iMac. The fastest path to something shareable is a single HTML viewer that loads one of those JSON files and renders the cards \'97 essentially the Seville widget we built in the early sessions, but now loading from a verified JSON rather than having data baked in. That could be built in one session and would let you show the research to anyone with a browser.\
\
Where I think you should go next\
Rather than running Lisbon immediately, I'd suggest two things:\
First \'97 build the simple viewer. One HTML file that loads a city pack JSON and renders filterable cards. Test it with the Barcelona pack. This turns the research from a file in a folder into something you can actually show people and get feedback on.\
Second \'97 decide on scope before adding more cities. Is this a two-city proof of concept you want to show to potential collaborators or investors? A personal project you want to keep building quietly? A product you intend to launch publicly? The answer changes what you should build next significantly.\
The pipeline is in good shape. The data is good. The next constraint isn't more research \'97 it's building something people can see.\
What's your sense of where this should go?\
