\cf2 Really important question \'97 and one that gets to the heart of what makes LocalBite genuinely valuable versus just another anglophone restaurant guide with a nicer attribution model.\
\
The core problem\
The best local knowledge is written in the local language. Rosa Rod\'f3n at Ara.cat Mengem writing in Catalan about where to eat in Gr\'e0cia is closer to ground truth than The Infatuation's Barcelona Hit List. But if your audience is primarily English-speaking, that knowledge is locked behind a language barrier that most users won't cross.\
The current pipeline captures it \'97 the both-pool signal exists precisely because we're reading Catalan and Spanish sources. But the product doesn't surface it in a way an English speaker can actually use. The quote field in the JSON contains a paraphrased English translation, but it's thin \'97 one sentence, no context about who the writer is or why they matter.\
\
Four approaches worth considering\
Approach 1 \'97 Machine translation of the source quote\
The simplest fix. When extracting from a Catalan or Spanish source, translate the writer's actual words into English rather than paraphrasing. Modern translation is good enough that Rosa Rod\'f3n's voice comes through reasonably well in English. The card then shows the translated quote with a clear label \'97 "Translated from Catalan" \'97 so the user knows the provenance.\
This is already partially happening in the pipeline \'97 the extraction prompt produces English paraphrases of non-English sources. The improvement would be making the translation more faithful and labelling it explicitly rather than presenting it as if it were originally written in English.\
Approach 2 \'97 Writer profiles as the bridge\
Rather than just showing a quote, build a short profile of each source writer that explains why they matter in their local context. Rosa Rod\'f3n is a food critic at Ara.cat, Catalonia's leading independent newspaper, writing for a Catalan-speaking readership with no advertorial relationships. That sentence gives an English-speaking user more confidence in her recommendation than the quote itself does.\
This would be a new field in the JSON \'97 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 writer_profile
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  \'97 populated during the pipeline run. The viewer would show it on the source card or in a dedicated sources page. A reader who doesn't know what Ara.cat is gets the context they need to trust the recommendation.\
Approach 3 \'97 The cross-source signal as the product\
Lean into the both-pool methodology as the primary user-facing feature rather than the individual quotes. The pitch to an English-speaking user isn't "here's what a Catalan writer said" \'97 it's "this restaurant appears in both English and Catalan food media independently, which means locals and visitors agree." The user doesn't need to read Catalan to understand that signal.\
This reframes the language barrier as a strength. The fact that we're reading sources most users can't access is what makes the cross-pool confirmation meaningful. An English-speaking user would never discover Ara.cat on their own \'97 but LocalBite synthesises that knowledge into a signal they can immediately understand and trust.\
Approach 4 \'97 Bilingual card display\
For each non-English quote, show both the original and the translation. A user who speaks Spanish or Catalan sees the original and appreciates the authenticity. A user who doesn't still gets the translation. The presence of the original signals that this isn't made up \'97 it's a real thing a real person wrote in a real publication.\
This is the most ambitious display approach but also the most honest. It treats the multilingual sourcing as a feature to show off rather than a problem to hide.\
\
The deeper question this raises\
The language barrier problem is actually a symptom of a bigger editorial question: what is LocalBite's relationship to local writers?\
Right now we're extracting from their work without any relationship with them. That's ethically fine \'97 we link to their articles and attribute clearly \'97 but it means we're dependent on whatever they happened to write about and whether Jina can fetch it.\
A stronger model over time would be direct relationships with local writers \'97 commissioning short "where I actually eat" pieces in their own language, which LocalBite then translates and presents with full attribution and a link to the writer's own work. This turns LocalBite from an aggregator into a publisher with a global network of local food writers. That's a significantly more defensible product.\
That's a longer-term vision, but it's worth naming because Approach 2 (writer profiles) is a step toward it. Once you're writing profiles of writers, you're already thinking about them as editorial relationships rather than just data sources.\
\
My recommendation for now\
Start with Approach 1 (faithful translation with clear labelling) combined with Approach 2 (writer profiles) as a new JSON field. Both can be added to the v5 prompt with modest changes. Approach 3 (cross-source signal as the product) should inform the viewer design \'97 the both-pool badge should be prominent and explained, not just a colour-coded border that users have to decode.\
Approach 4 (bilingual display) is worth holding for a future version once you know whether users are finding the translated quotes valuable at all.\
The direct writer relationship model is the right long-term direction but requires resources and relationships that aren't available yet. It's worth keeping in mind as the north star.\
\
Does this match how you're thinking about it, or is there a specific aspect of the language problem you want to dig into further?\
