\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 They run from Anthropic's servers, not your desktop.\
When Claude Code runs a web search, it calls Anthropic's web search tool which executes the search on Anthropic's infrastructure and returns results to Claude Code. Similarly when Claude Code fetches a URL via Jina, the request goes from Anthropic's servers to Jina's servers \'97 your Mac is just displaying the conversation, not doing any of the actual fetching or searching.\
This has a few practical implications for LocalBite:\
Privacy \'97 the search queries and fetched article content pass through Anthropic's systems. For our use case this is fine \'97 we're searching for publicly available restaurant recommendations, nothing sensitive.\
Speed \'97 the latency you see between a search being issued and results appearing is network latency between Anthropic's servers and the search provider, plus the model processing time. Your internet connection speed doesn't affect it.\
CORS \'97 this is why the browser widget couldn't call the Anthropic API directly. A browser runs on your machine and is subject to browser security rules that block cross-origin requests. Claude Code runs server-side so those restrictions don't apply.\
Jina fetches \'97 same story. When the pipeline fetches 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 https://r.jina.ai/https://hespress.com/...
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  that request originates from Anthropic's infrastructure, not your iMac. Hespress sees a request from Anthropic's IP addresses, not yours.\
This is also why Claude Code works even if your home internet connection is slow \'97 the heavy lifting happens on Anthropic's end.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \
