\cf2 Claude Code is a hybrid \'97 the two parts run in different places:\
What runs on your Mac The Claude Code application itself \'97 the terminal interface you type into, the file reading and writing, the bash commands. When Claude Code writes 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 localbite-marrakesh-working.json
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  to your localbite folder, that file write happens on your Mac. When it reads a file, it reads from your Mac's filesystem. The 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 >
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  prompt you see is a local process running on your machine.\
What runs on Anthropic's servers The intelligence \'97 every time Claude Code thinks, searches, decides what to do next, or generates text, that computation happens on Anthropic's servers. Your Mac sends the context (what's happened so far, what files contain, what search results showed) up to Anthropic, the model processes it, and the response comes back down to your terminal.\
The practical implication This is why Claude Code needs an internet connection to work \'97 it's constantly sending context up to Anthropic and receiving instructions back. But the files it creates, the scripts it runs, the bash commands it executes \'97 all of that happens locally on your Mac.\
Think of it like this: your Mac is the hands, Anthropic's servers are the brain. The hands do the physical work (file writes, terminal commands) but wait for instructions from the brain before each action. Every permission prompt you see \'97 "do you want to proceed?" \'97 is your Mac asking whether to carry out an instruction it just received from the server.\
This is also why context compression happens mid-run \'97 when the conversation gets very long, the amount of context being sent up to Anthropic with each request becomes large and expensive, so Claude Code compresses it to keep things manageable.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
