\cf2 Good time to think it through. Let me lay out the key decisions before we start building.\
\
What the viewer needs to do at minimum\
Load a city pack JSON file and render the restaurants as browsable cards. Filter by neighbourhood, price, language pool, and source. Show the attribution clearly \'97 writer name, publication, article link. Surface the both-pool signal prominently. Work in a browser without any server or database.\
That's it for v1. Everything else is a later addition.\
\
The key design decisions\
Decision 1 \'97 Single city or multi-city?\
The simplest viewer loads one JSON file and shows one city. A more useful viewer lets you switch between cities. Given we now have packs for Valencia, Barcelona, Fes, and soon Marrakesh, a city selector is worth building from the start \'97 it's a small addition that makes the viewer feel like a product rather than a demo.\
Decision 2 \'97 Where does the JSON live?\
Three options:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls128\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Baked in \'97 JSON data embedded directly in the HTML file. Simple, works offline, but requires rebuilding the file every time you add a city. This is what the early Seville widget did.\
\ls128\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Loaded from local files \'97 the HTML file fetches JSON from the same folder. Works when opened from your Mac but won't work if you share the HTML file with someone else.\
\ls128\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Loaded from a URL \'97 JSON files hosted somewhere publicly (GitHub Pages, a simple CDN). The HTML fetches them at runtime. This is the right approach for anything shareable.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 For a first viewer that you can show to people, GitHub Pages is the easiest free hosting solution. You'd put the JSON files and the HTML viewer in a GitHub repository and they'd be accessible at a public URL immediately.\
Decision 3 \'97 How does it handle the new v5 fields?\
The Marrakesh pack will have fields that Barcelona and Valencia don't \'97 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 writer_profile
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 , 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 name_arabic
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 , 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 quote_language
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 , 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 price_currency
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  in MAD. The viewer needs to handle these gracefully \'97 showing them when present, hiding them when absent, without breaking for older city packs.\
Decision 4 \'97 What does the card look like?\
The early Seville widget had a good card structure \'97 restaurant name, neighbourhood, price, quote, writer attribution, source link. For v5 we should add:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls129\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Writer profile on hover or expandable \'97 the 2-3 sentence context that explains why this source is credible\
\ls129\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Quote language label \'97 "Translated from French" where applicable\
\ls129\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Both-pool explanation in plain English \'97 not just a badge but a tooltip or label saying "Confirmed by writers in two languages"\
\ls129\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Cuisine type tag\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Decision 5 \'97 Static HTML or React?\
Static HTML with vanilla JavaScript is simpler to share, works anywhere, and requires no build step. React is more powerful for complex filtering and state but adds complexity. Given the viewer is primarily a browsable card list with filters, vanilla HTML is the right choice for v1.\
\
What I'd suggest building\
A single HTML file that:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls130\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Has a city selector at the top loading from a list of available JSON packs\
\ls130\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fetches the selected city's JSON from GitHub (or locally for testing)\
\ls130\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Renders filterable cards with neighbourhood, price, pool, and cuisine filters\
\ls130\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Shows writer attribution with a profile tooltip\
\ls130\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Highlights both-pool entries prominently with a plain-English explanation\
\ls130\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Handles both MAD and EUR price levels gracefully\
\ls130\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	7	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Shows quote language labels for translated content\
