\cf2 Good question \'97 and the honest answer is yes and no depending on how you define production.\
\
What GitHub Pages is good for\
GitHub Pages is genuinely production-grade for a static viewer \'97 a read-only website that loads JSON files and renders them in a browser. It's free, fast, reliable, and used by many real products for exactly this kind of use case. The viewer we'd build is a static site \'97 no server, no database, no user accounts \'97 and GitHub Pages handles static sites very well.\
For showing the project to friends, potential collaborators, or early users, GitHub Pages is entirely appropriate. It gives you a real URL, works on any device, and requires no ongoing maintenance.\
\
What GitHub Pages can't do\
As soon as the product needs any of the following, GitHub Pages is no longer sufficient:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls135\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
User accounts \'97 if users want to save favourites, create lists, or have personalised experiences\
\ls135\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A database \'97 if restaurant data needs to be searchable across cities, updated in real time, or queried dynamically\
\ls135\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Server-side logic \'97 if you want to run the pipeline automatically, process user submissions, or handle payments\
\ls135\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A custom domain with full control \'97 you can use a custom domain with GitHub Pages but it has limitations\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 These are all things the original spec at 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 local-eats-spec.md
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  contemplates. Supabase for the database, a proper backend for the pipeline automation, user authentication \'97 none of that fits on GitHub Pages.\
\
The honest architecture picture\
There are really three stages:\
Stage 1 \'97 GitHub Pages (now) Static viewer, JSON files hosted publicly, no backend. Good for showing people, getting feedback, testing the card design and filtering. Free, zero infrastructure.\
Stage 2 \'97 Hybrid (6-12 months) GitHub Pages or similar for the frontend, Supabase for the database, a simple API for serving city packs. The pipeline still runs manually in Claude Code but uploads results to Supabase rather than saving JSON files locally. User accounts possible. Custom domain.\
Stage 3 \'97 Full product (12+ months) Automated pipeline, proper backend, mobile app, potentially monetised. This is what the spec describes.\
\
My recommendation\
Build on GitHub Pages now without thinking of it as a permanent production decision. It gets something real in front of people quickly, at zero cost, with no infrastructure to manage. When the product outgrows it \'97 which will happen if it gains users \'97 migrating to a proper backend is straightforward because the JSON schema we've built is already well-structured for a database.\
The worst outcome would be spending months building infrastructure before you know whether anyone wants to use the product. GitHub Pages lets you find out cheaply.\
Shall we set up GitHub Pages and build the viewer while we wait for the Marrakesh run to finish?\
