\cf2 Yes \'97 GitHub Pages serves regular websites and a well-built HTML viewer works perfectly on mobile browsers. iPhones and Android phones both handle it fine. No app needed.\
The key is building the viewer with responsive design from the start \'97 meaning the layout adapts to the screen size. On a desktop you'd see a sidebar with filters and cards to the right. On a phone the same content stacks vertically \'97 filters collapse into a menu at the top, cards fill the full width below.\
This is straightforward with CSS and doesn't require any additional infrastructure. The same HTML file that works on your Mac also works on a phone when accessed via the GitHub Pages URL.\
\
What mobile-first means for the viewer design\
A few specific decisions worth making before building:\
Cards need to be finger-friendly \'97 tap targets at least 44px, enough padding that the source link and filter buttons are easy to hit on a small screen.\
Filters need a mobile treatment \'97 on desktop a sidebar makes sense, but on mobile a horizontal scrollable filter row or a collapsible filter panel works better than a sidebar that takes up half the screen.\
The writer profile tooltip \'97 on desktop a hover works fine, but on mobile there's no hover. An expandable section within the card is the right approach for mobile.\
The city selector \'97 a simple dropdown works on both desktop and mobile without any special treatment.\
\
The limitation\
GitHub Pages serves the site but doesn't give you a native app experience \'97 no push notifications, no offline mode, no home screen icon with your branding. For a v1 that's completely fine. If LocalBite ever becomes a real product with regular users, a progressive web app (PWA) layer can be added later to enable those features without needing to build a separate iOS or Android app.\
\
Bottom line\
GitHub Pages plus responsive HTML is a legitimate mobile-compatible solution for a v1 viewer. It won't feel like a native app but it will work well in a mobile browser, which is how most people discover new products anyway \'97 someone sends them a link and they open it on their phone.\
