\cf2 Good question to ask before committing. Here's an honest breakdown.\
\
The work involved\
City selector and JSON loading \'97 a dropdown that lists available cities and fetches the right JSON file when selected. Straightforward, about 2-3 hours including handling the different schemas between v4 (Barcelona, Valencia) and v5 (Marrakesh, Fes) gracefully.\
Card design \'97 the core restaurant card with name, neighbourhood, price, cuisine, quote, writer attribution, source link, both-pool badge, quote language label, and writer profile expandable section. This is the most design-intensive piece. Probably 4-6 hours to get right across both desktop and mobile.\
Filter system \'97 neighbourhood, price, language pool, source, cuisine type filters that work across different city schemas. The neighbourhood lists differ by city, the price currency differs (\'80 vs MAD), and not all fields exist in all city packs. Handling this gracefully adds complexity. Probably 3-4 hours.\
Responsive layout \'97 making the sidebar collapse on mobile, ensuring cards are finger-friendly, testing on different screen sizes. Probably 2-3 hours.\
Both-pool explanation \'97 the plain-English tooltip or expandable label explaining what cross-language confirmation means. Small feature, 1 hour.\
Writer profile display \'97 expandable section on mobile, hover panel on desktop. 1-2 hours.\
GitHub setup and deployment \'97 creating the repository, uploading files, configuring GitHub Pages, testing the public URL. 1-2 hours the first time.\
Testing and refinement \'97 loading all four city packs, checking edge cases (restaurants with no neighbourhood, MAD prices, Arabic names), fixing display issues. 2-3 hours.\
\
Total estimate\
Minimum viable viewer \'97 city selector, cards, basic filters, mobile-responsive: 1.5 to 2 days of focused work across 2-3 sessions.\
Polished viewer \'97 all of the above plus writer profiles, quote language labels, both-pool explanation, smooth animations, well-tested across devices: 3 to 4 days across 4-5 sessions.\
\
What affects the estimate most\
The biggest variable is the schema differences between city packs. Valencia and Barcelona were built with v3/v4 schemas, Fes and Marrakesh with v5. The viewer needs to handle both gracefully \'97 showing writer profiles when present, hiding them when absent, displaying MAD prices differently from EUR prices, handling 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 name_arabic
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  where it exists. Getting this right without brittle code takes more time than building for a single consistent schema.\
The second variable is how much design polish you want. A functional viewer that works well but looks basic could be built in one long session. A viewer that looks genuinely good and feels like a real product takes longer.\
\
My recommendation\
Build the minimum viable viewer first \'97 one session, get something working on GitHub Pages with all four cities loadable. Then refine in subsequent sessions based on what you see and what feedback you get from anyone you show it to.\
The minimum viable viewer is probably a 3-4 hour Claude Code session. The polished version is another 2-3 sessions after that.\
Does that timeline feel workable, or would you like to scope it differently?\
