\fs28 \cf6 Reconciled LocalBite map vision with prior Seville implementation experience\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Reconciled LocalBite map vision with prior Seville implementation experience\
\
Good question \'97 there are some important differences between what we'd build now and the early Seville map work.\
What was different about the Seville map\
The Seville map was a proof of concept built directly into a self-contained widget with the restaurant data baked in. It used a simple mapping library (likely Leaflet) with hardcoded coordinates that were either fabricated or estimated from neighbourhood names. It was a demo, not a real map.\
The core problem was that we had no actual GPS coordinates for any restaurant \'97 just neighbourhood names. So the pins were approximate at best.\
What's different now\
We have the same problem \'97 no GPS coordinates in any of the four city packs. The JSON schema has name, neighbourhood, and cuisine but no latitude/longitude. Before building a map view we'd need to solve the coordinate problem.\
There are three approaches:\
\
Approach 1 \'97 Google Maps Place IDs\
Add a 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 place_id
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  field to each restaurant entry during the pipeline run. Google Maps Place IDs are stable unique identifiers that map directly to a pin on Google Maps. With a Place ID you can:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls192\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Link directly to the restaurant on Google Maps\
\ls192\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Embed a map with accurate pins using the Google Maps JavaScript API\
\ls192\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Get accurate coordinates automatically\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The downside is you need a Google Maps API key which has a small cost beyond the free tier, and adding Place IDs requires a manual or semi-automated lookup pass for all 138 restaurants across four cities.\
Approach 2 \'97 Geocode from restaurant name and neighbourhood\
Use a geocoding API (Google Geocoding, Nominatim/OpenStreetMap which is free) to convert "Nomad, Medina, Marrakesh" into coordinates automatically. This could be built into the pipeline as a post-processing step. Accuracy is good for well-known restaurants, less reliable for small local places.\
Approach 3 \'97 Leaflet with neighbourhood-level pins\
Use OpenStreetMap via Leaflet (free, no API key) with pins placed at neighbourhood centroids rather than exact restaurant locations. Clicking a pin shows the restaurant cards for that neighbourhood. Less precise but requires no coordinate data and no API key.\
\
My recommendation\
Approach 3 is the right starting point \'97 it gets a map into the viewer quickly with no API costs and no coordinate lookup work. Neighbourhood-level clustering is actually a reasonable UX for a travel tool \'97 you're often thinking "what's good in the medina" not "show me the exact address."\
Approach 1 (Place IDs) is the right long-term solution but requires a data enrichment pass on all four city packs first. Worth planning for but not the immediate next step.\
How it would work in the viewer\
A toggle button in the filters bar \'97 "Map view / List view". In map view the cards are replaced by a Leaflet map with neighbourhood cluster pins. Clicking a cluster opens a small popup showing the restaurant cards for that neighbourhood. The filters still work \'97 filtering by price or cuisine updates which pins are visible on the map.\
This is probably a half-day build once we decide on the approach. Want to go with Approach 3 to start?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
