\fs28 \cf6 Marshaled critical analysis of Approach 3's limitations\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Marshaled critical analysis of Approach 3's limitations\
\
Here is an honest and complete list:\
Accuracy problems\
The pins would sit at neighbourhood centroids \'97 the geographic centre of a neighbourhood \'97 not at the actual restaurant location. For a large neighbourhood like Eixample in Barcelona, the centroid could be 500 metres or more from the actual restaurant. A user trying to navigate to a specific place would be misled. For Fes el-Bali, where everything is technically in the same neighbourhood, almost every restaurant would stack on a single pin.\
Clustering makes the map nearly useless for some cities\
Fes has 9 of its 10 restaurants in Fes el-Bali. Marrakesh has 9 of 14 in the Medina. All pins would overlap on a single point, which is misleading and visually poor. The map would tell users almost nothing about where these restaurants actually are in relation to each other.\
No navigation value\
The core use case for a map in a travel product is "I'm standing here, what's nearby." Neighbourhood centroid pins can't answer that question. A user in the Born neighbourhood of Barcelona looking at the map would see a pin somewhere in the middle of the Born and not know if the restaurant is 50 metres away or 800 metres away.\
No integration with mapping apps\
With real coordinates or Place IDs you can offer "Open in Google Maps" or "Open in Apple Maps" links that drop a pin at the exact location. With centroids you can't do this honestly \'97 sending a user to the centre of Eixample and saying "the restaurant is here" is actively wrong.\
Maintenance overhead with no clear upgrade path\
The neighbourhood centroid coordinates would be hardcoded by city. When you add a new city you'd have to manually look up and add centroid coordinates for every neighbourhood in that city. And when you eventually switch to real coordinates, you'd have to rebuild the whole approach rather than just enriching the existing data.\
False sense of precision\
A pin on a map implies geographic accuracy even when users know it's approximate. Research shows that people trust visual information on maps more than they trust text disclaimers. A "these are approximate" label doesn't fully counteract the visual implication of a pin.\
Doesn't solve the actual user problem\
The reason a traveller wants a map is to understand spatial relationships between restaurants \'97 which ones are close together, which ones are near where they're staying. Neighbourhood centroids preserve some of this for large cities with many distinct neighbourhoods (Barcelona) but destroy it for compact medina cities (Fes, Marrakesh) where everything is a short walk from everything else and the interesting spatial information is at the street level, not the neighbourhood level.\
The bottom line\
Approach 3 is a reasonable-looking map that doesn't actually do what a map is for. It would look like a feature but function as decoration. For Barcelona with its distinct spread-out neighbourhoods it's less bad \'97 but for the two Moroccan cities it would be actively misleading.\
The honest conclusion is that a map without real coordinates isn't worth building. The effort is better spent on a data enrichment pass to add Place IDs or coordinates to the existing city packs, then building the map properly. That enrichment pass for 138 restaurants across four cities is probably a 2-3 hour Claude Code task \'97 looking up each restaurant by name and city in the Google Maps API or even just using Nominatim (free) to geocode name plus neighbourhood plus city.\
Would you like to do the enrichment pass first and then build the map properly?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
