\cf2 The viewer and documentation work here in this chat uses whatever model powers claude.ai \'97 currently Sonnet 4.6.\
\
Is extended thinking helping us?\
For the pipeline runs \'97 probably yes. The pipeline prompt is long and complex, with many interdependent rules (diversity gate, concentration cap, tier assignment, quote quality rules). Extended thinking helps Claude Code reason through edge cases more carefully \'97 for example correctly firing the concentration cap on Maroclovers in the Rabat run, or correctly handling the sibling edition check.\
For the chat work we do here \'97 building prompts, reviewing results, writing documentation \'97 extended thinking is less critical. Standard Sonnet 4.6 handles this well.\
\
Would Opus 4.6 be better for the pipeline?\
Opus is more capable at complex reasoning but significantly slower and more expensive. For a pipeline that runs 20-30 searches, fetches 8-12 articles, extracts data, scores confidence tiers, and produces structured JSON \'97 Opus might produce marginally better source selection decisions. But Sonnet 4.6 with extended thinking has performed well across all four Morocco city runs so far with only minor errors (Benyamna wrong coords, Marea Ghana) that were in the geocoding script not the pipeline.\
\
My honest recommendation\
Stay with Sonnet 4.6. The pipeline runs are performing well and the errors we've seen are geocoding issues not pipeline reasoning issues. The main friction has been rate limits and deployment, not model quality.\
If you find the pipeline making poor source selection decisions or missing obvious candidates in future cities, that's the signal to try Opus. For now Sonnet 4.6 is the right balance of capability, speed, and cost.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
