\cf2 Great question \'97 and thinking ahead to automation changes the answer significantly.\
\
What changes in a fully automated pipeline\
Manual geocoding goes away \'97 replaced by the improved Nominatim v3 script with bounding box queries. Manual removals go away \'97 the pipeline's own recommendations are auto-accepted. The human role shrinks to just reviewing the final summary and pushing to GitHub.\
In that scenario the bottleneck shifts from human judgment to pipeline reliability and cost per city run.\
\
Cost and speed on Claude Pro\
On Claude Pro you don't pay per token \'97 you have a usage limit that resets every 5 hours. The cost question is really about how many cities you can run per session before hitting the limit.\
Extended thinking consumes significantly more of your Pro limit per run than standard mode because it generates additional reasoning tokens that count toward your quota. That's why the Barcelona v4 run hit the limit before the export step.\
For 10 cities in one session, extended thinking would almost certainly exhaust your limit partway through \'97 probably around city 3 or 4.\
\
The right model for automated batch runs\
For a fully automated 10-city batch the ideal setup would be:\
Haiku 3.5 for the geocoding and file operations \'97 it's the fastest and cheapest model, perfectly capable of running the Node.js script, copying files, and pushing to GitHub.\
Sonnet 4.6 without extended thinking for the pipeline runs \'97 standard Sonnet is fast, reliable, and uses roughly half the Pro limit per run compared to extended thinking. Across 10 cities that's the difference between hitting the limit at city 4 versus city 8.\
Opus only for cities where source selection is genuinely difficult \'97 Arabic-primary cities, very small cities with thin coverage, or cities where you suspect the pipeline is missing important local sources.\
\
The honest trade-off\
Extended thinking catches edge cases better \'97 the concentration cap firing correctly on Maroclovers, the sibling edition check, the riad editorial rule. In a fully automated pipeline with no human review those edge cases matter more, not less. Removing extended thinking to save quota might produce slightly weaker source selection decisions that nobody catches.\
My recommendation for the automated scenario:\
Run Sonnet 4.6 without extended thinking for the main pipeline, but keep the concentration cap, diversity gate, and tier assignment rules exactly as they are. The rules themselves catch most edge cases \'97 extended thinking mainly helps when the rules conflict or are ambiguous. For well-documented cities in countries like France, Italy, or Spain where sources are plentiful, the rules will fire correctly without needing extended reasoning.\
For Morocco specifically \'97 given thin source pools and structural Arabic gaps \'97 extended thinking is worth keeping because the pipeline needs to reason harder about what constitutes an acceptable source.\
\
Bottom line\
For a 10-city automated batch in a well-documented country: Sonnet 4.6 standard (no extended thinking), auto-accept pipeline recommendations, Nominatim v3 geocoding. You'd likely complete 8-10 cities before hitting the Pro limit.\
For Morocco or other thin-coverage regions: keep extended thinking but run one city at a time.\
Consider Claude Max 5x ($100/month) if you're running batches regularly \'97 at that point the per-city economics change and extended thinking becomes affordable across all cities.\
