What this means practically\
The most significant search-related differences are:\
1. Valencia has no formal search plan \'97 the v3 pipeline didn't write queries to a file first, so we have no record of what was searched and no duplicate detection was applied.\
2. Barcelona has no Arabic searches \'97 the prompt didn't include Arabic angle queries. For a Spanish city this doesn't matter since there's no Arabic food writing scene for Barcelona.\
3. Fes has no Arabic direct fetch \'97 it was run before that v5 feature was added. Given Hespress and Goud.ma both failed in all subsequent cities this probably didn't cost any restaurants.\
4. Chefchaouen's relaxed diversity gate \'97 the most permissive of any city. Intentional and documented but means the sourcing standard is lower than Barcelona or Marrakesh.\
\
Any of these worth fixing?\
The only one with potential practical impact is Valencia's lack of a formal search plan \'97 we don't know if important sources were missed because there was no structured approach. A v5 re-run of Valencia would address this properly.\
Everything else is either documented in the research summaries, handled gracefully by the viewer, or reflects intentional editorial decisions for that specific city's characteristics.\
