The deeper problem\
These aren't just edge cases \'97 they represent a fundamental tension in automation:\
The pipeline produces recommendations but humans have been making the final calls. In every city run there have been 2-5 judgment calls that went beyond what the prompt rules specified. The prompt handles the 80% case well. The 20% requires context that is currently in your head and in the research summaries.\
For automation to work reliably you'd need to either:\
A \'97 Codify all the edge cases into the prompt Make the riad rule more specific. Define exactly when a hotel restaurant passes. Specify what "dish-level specificity" means precisely. Add explicit rules for borderline source classifications. This would make the prompt longer and more brittle.\
B \'97 Accept lower quality for automated cities Run the automation knowing some edge cases will be handled less well than manual runs. Document this as a known limitation. Review the output afterwards rather than before publishing.\
C \'97 Build a post-processing quality layer After the pipeline runs automatically, a separate lightweight review step checks for known problem patterns \'97 restaurants with null neighbourhoods, riad entries with weak quotes, suspicious geocoding results \'97 and flags them for human attention before publishing.\
\
The geocoding problem specifically\
The research summaries document specific false positives that were caught manually:\
