\ls297\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Rabat: Maroclovers 9 entries 
\f2 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  capped to 4 (5 rejected)\
\ls297\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Chefchaouen: S3 at 29% 
\f2 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  not fired (1% under threshold)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 In automated mode Chefchaouen would have been fine. But a city where the dominant blogger had 31% of entries would auto-reject based on a 1% difference. This threshold sensitivity is acceptable in manual runs where you can override \'97 in automated runs it would produce inconsistent results across cities with no explanation.\
\
What the research summaries reveal about automation readiness\
Reading across all six summaries, the cities that would automate cleanly are ones where:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls298\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Multiple strong sources surfaced easily\
\ls298\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
No concentration cap needed\
\ls298\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
No riad or hotel restaurant edge cases\
\ls298\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Geocoding hit rate was high with few false positives\
\ls298\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Both-pool count was healthy\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Barcelona (14 both-pool, 9 sources, cap not fired) would have automated well. Chefchaouen (11 Tier A, strong multi-source consensus, zero geocoding false positives) would have automated well despite thin local coverage.\
Rabat (zero both-pool, cap fired, geocoding false positive) would have produced a noticeably weaker result without human intervention.\
\
My honest assessment\
The research summaries reveal that automation is viable for cities with strong source diversity but carries meaningful quality risk for thin-source cities. The intentional decisions aren't random \'97 they cluster around three scenarios:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls299\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Thin source pools \'97 when one source dominates, human judgment about concentration and quality matters more\
\ls299\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Geocoding false positives \'97 the v3 bounding box script handles these better now but doesn't eliminate them\
\ls299\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Editorial category edge cases \'97 riads, hotel restaurants, bookshops, wine bars \'97 the pipeline flags these but humans make the final call\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 For a 10-city well-documented European batch, scenarios 1 and 3 would be rare. Scenario 2 would still occur occasionally even with v3.\
The practical recommendation:\
Design automation with a human checkpoint after the pipeline runs but before publishing. Not a full review of every restaurant \'97 just a scan of the flagged entries and a check of the summary statistics (both-pool count, concentration cap status, source count). This takes 5 minutes per city and catches the cases where human judgment genuinely matters.\
Full unattended automation \'97 pipeline runs, auto-accepts, geocodes, publishes \'97 is achievable for well-documented cities but will occasionally produce Rabat-quality packs without you knowing until after they're live. Whether that's acceptable depends on how important quality consistency is to you at this stage.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
