The gap is significant\
In a compact city like Chefchaouen the current map is actually useful \'97 everything is within 5 minutes walk so proximity doesn't differentiate. But in Barcelona with 52 restaurants spread across Eixample, Gr\'e0cia, El Born, Poble Sec, and Barceloneta \'97 a user in El Born doesn't want to see the Sants-Montju\'efc restaurants at all. The current map shows all 52 with no proximity ranking.\
\
What would solve the use case\
Option 1 \'97 Device location + radius filter\
Use the browser's Geolocation API to get the user's current position, then filter the map to show only restaurants within a chosen radius (500m, 1km, 2km). The map re-centres on the user with a location pin. This is the most direct solution.\
Works entirely in the browser \'97 no server needed. Requires real coordinates on every restaurant (which Morocco cities now have, Spain cities don't yet). Requires user to grant location permission.\
Option 2 \'97 "Near me" list view\
Skip the map entirely. A "Near me" button uses geolocation to sort the card list by distance from the user's current location, closest first. Each card shows the distance ("320m away"). No map rendering needed.\
This is actually more useful than the map for making a decision \'97 you see the full card with quote, sources, and both-pool signal sorted by proximity. The map just shows you a pin.\
Option 3 \'97 Neighbourhood-first navigation\
No geolocation at all. A prominent neighbourhood selector on the landing page \'97 "I'm in the Medina / Gueliz / El Born" \'97 that filters immediately to just those restaurants. Faster than geolocation, works without permissions, and matches how travellers actually think ("I'm exploring the medina today").\
This works even without exact coordinates since it filters by the neighbourhood field in the JSON.\
\
