\cf2 Good question to think through carefully before committing. Let me work through the risks and considerations first, then the implementation plan.\
\
Risks and considerations\
1. Geolocation permission friction\
On mobile browsers, requesting location permission triggers a system dialog \'97 "LocalBite would like to use your location." This happens the first time the button is tapped. If the user is planning from home and sees the "you're not in Marrakesh" message immediately after granting permission, they may feel the permission request was wasted or misleading. Some users will deny the permission entirely, which means the feature never works for them even when they arrive.\
Mitigation: Only request location permission after the user taps the button, not on page load. Make the button label clear \'97 "Find restaurants near me" rather than just a location icon \'97 so users understand what they're enabling.\
2. The bounding box is not a perfect proxy for "in the city"\
A user on a flight to Marrakesh crossing over Morocco might trigger the "you're in range" condition. A user staying in a resort 15km outside Marrakesh might be outside the bounding box but still want to plan dinner. The bounding box we designed for geocoding (preventing false positives) is tighter than what makes sense for "are you visiting this city."\
Mitigation: Use a slightly larger bounding box for the location check than for geocoding \'97 perhaps 20-30km radius from city centre rather than the tight medina box. This is a separate parameter from the geocoding bounding box.\
3. GPS accuracy in medinas\
Chefchaouen and Fes el-Bali have dense building coverage that degrades GPS accuracy significantly. A user in the Fes medina might get a location reading that's 200-500 metres off. With only 10 restaurants spread across the medina this could make nearby restaurants appear farther than they are.\
This isn't a blocker but worth noting in documentation \'97 and it's why the "near me" distance sort is less reliable in dense medina environments than in open European cities.\
4. The message copy needs to be carefully worded\
"You're not currently in Marrakesh" could read as dismissive or unhelpful. A user planning a trip might feel the app is telling them they're doing something wrong. The message needs to be warm, informative, and actionable.\
Draft: "Looks like you're planning ahead \'97 this feature works best once you're in Marrakesh. Save it for when you arrive." This acknowledges the planning use case positively rather than just refusing.\
5. No both-pool or quality signal in the location dot view\
The blue dot tells you where you are but doesn't change which restaurant to choose. A user standing 200m from three restaurants still needs to make a quality judgment. The current card view with quotes and source attribution is better for that decision than a map pin. This reinforces the point that the blue dot supplements the existing experience rather than replacing it.\
6. Privacy\
Requesting GPS coordinates is a meaningful privacy ask. The browser handles the permission dialog but LocalBite should never send location data to any server. Since everything runs in the browser this is naturally satisfied \'97 the coordinates stay on the device. Worth noting in an eventual privacy/about page.\
7. Battery and performance on mobile\
Geolocation on mobile consumes battery. The implementation should use a single one-shot location request rather than continuous tracking. No need to update the blue dot as the user walks around \'97 they can tap the button again if needed.\
