\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  integration that's well tested across all mobile browsers\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls307\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A native blue dot ("My Location") button that's one line to enable \'97 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 map.setOptions(\{myLocationButton: true\})
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 \
\ls307\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Familiar UX that users already understand from Google Maps itself\
\ls307\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Better GPS accuracy handling and graceful degradation built in\
\ls307\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Place details and street-level accuracy that Leaflet with OpenStreetMap doesn't match in dense medinas\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The proximity feature on Google Maps would be roughly 2 hours of work versus the 5.5 hours estimated for Leaflet. The hard parts (permission handling, distance calculation, blue dot styling, mobile testing) are largely handled by Google's SDK.\
\
The trade-offs\
Terms of service \'97 as discussed earlier, Google requires results to be displayed on a Google Map. Using Google Maps for display and OpenStreetMap for tile data is a terms violation. Switching to Google Maps means committing to Google's ecosystem.\
Cost \'97 Google Maps JavaScript API includes a $200 monthly credit which covers roughly 28,000 map loads per month. At LocalBite's current scale (friends and early testers) this is free in practice. If the product grows to thousands of daily users the cost becomes real.\
Vendor lock-in \'97 once the viewer is built on Google Maps switching back to Leaflet is a significant rewrite. You'd be dependent on Google's pricing decisions going forward.\
Data privacy \'97 Google Maps sends user location data to Google's servers. Leaflet with OpenStreetMap keeps everything in the browser.\
\
