\cf2 You're right \'97 I flip-flopped and shouldn't have. Let me be direct about why Leaflet is the better long-term choice.\
The 3.5 hour difference is a one-time cost. Everything else about Google Maps is an ongoing consideration:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls309\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Vendor dependency that grows harder to escape as the codebase matures\
\ls309\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Cost exposure that becomes real if LocalBite succeeds\
\ls309\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Google's terms requiring their tiles \'97 constraining future infrastructure decisions\
\ls309\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
User location data going to Google's servers rather than staying in the browser\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Leaflet with OpenStreetMap has none of those ongoing costs. You pay the 3.5 hours once and own the solution cleanly.\
The 2 hours versus 5.5 hours comparison also somewhat overstates Google's advantage. The 5.5 hour estimate for Leaflet includes mobile testing time which would be needed for Google Maps too. The actual code difference is closer to 2 hours versus 3.5 hours \'97 the permission handling, message copy, and mobile testing are roughly equal either way.\
Stay with Leaflet. The proximity feature in 5.5 hours on a platform you control is better than the same feature in 2 hours on a platform you don't.\
I should have said this more clearly the first time rather than recommending the switch. Good catch.\
