\
Priority 3 \'97 Test F: Direct publication fetch vs search-to-fetch\
Third because it tests a potentially significant time saving. If we already know the high-quality publications for a city \'97 TimeOut Lisboa, Observador, Fugas do P\'fablico \'97 going directly to them via Jina rather than using searches to discover them could reduce the pipeline run time by 30-40% and reduce rate limit pressure. For a 10-city automated batch this compounds significantly.\
This also tests whether the search phase is actually finding the best publications or just the most SEO-optimized ones. A direct fetch of TimeOut Lisboa's restaurant section might yield higher-quality sources than search results pointing to TimeOut Lisboa would.\
Effort: Medium \'97 requires one additional Lisbon run with a modified pre-phase.\
\
Priority 4 \'97 Test E: Local language query volume\
Fourth because the both-pool signal is the core quality differentiator of LocalBite. If increasing Portuguese query volume from 3 to 6 meaningfully increases both-pool count, that's worth knowing before running a Portugal batch. But this is lower priority than Tests A and F because we already have evidence that local-language sources are the binding constraint \'97 the question is whether more local-language searches actually surfaces more local-language sources or just more of the same ones.\
Effort: Medium \'97 requires one additional Lisbon run.\
\
Priority 5 \'97 Test B: Year constraint vs no year constraint\
Fifth because the risk is asymmetric. The 2025-2026 recency constraint is fundamental to LocalBite's editorial proposition \'97 it's what makes the recommendations current rather than evergreen. Relaxing it even in search queries risks letting pre-2025 sources into the pipeline. The upside (finding a few more sources) is smaller than the downside (diluting the recency signal). Worth testing eventually but not urgently.\
Effort: Low \'97 observable from a single run by comparing sources found with and without year terms in queries.\
\
Priority 6 \'97 Test C: Aggregator pre-fetch vs no pre-fetch\
Last because the evidence already points to an answer. Across four Moroccan cities the pre-phase aggregator seed fetch produced zero useful writer names. For European cities it may perform better but the marginal value seems low \'97 the main 22 queries tend to surface publications directly, and the pre-phase adds 3-5 searches and 3 Jina fetches to every run. If Tests A and F both show that writer-first queries and direct publication fetches are more efficient, the pre-phase becomes redundant.\
Effort: Low \'97 observable from any run by tracking which sources came from pre-phase vs main queries.\
