\cf2 Good \'97 let me give you clear recommendations on all three.\
\
Query budget: Strategy A gets 30, Strategy B gets 36 (30 + 6 pre-mapping)\
The purpose of the pre-mapping phase in Strategy B is to find writers before writing the search plan \'97 it's a qualitatively different activity from the 30 standard queries. If we force Strategy B to absorb the pre-mapping within the same 30-query budget, it would have to reduce its standard angle coverage to accommodate it, which would make the comparison confounded \'97 we'd be measuring both the pre-mapping benefit and the reduced angle coverage simultaneously and couldn't separate the two effects.\
Keeping them separate means Strategy B's advantage (if any) is cleanly attributable to the pre-mapping phase. The 6 extra queries are a known, deliberate cost. If Strategy B produces meaningfully better results with those 6 extra queries, we can then ask whether 6 pre-mapping queries is worth it. That's a cleaner conclusion than any alternative.\
\
Observable metrics: Test D, B, and C \'97 not Test F\
All three of D, B, and C are observable from Strategy A's output with no extra runs:\
Test D (fetch discipline) \'97 definitely include. After Strategy A completes, audit every source in the final pack and check whether a Jina fetch is recorded for it in the search log before restaurants were extracted. This is the most important quality check and costs nothing extra.\
Test B (year constraint) \'97 include. After Strategy A, look at the search log and identify any queries that included year terms (2025, 2026) and note whether those queries returned fewer or different results than queries without year terms. Also check whether any sources the pipeline rejected on date grounds were ones that year-constrained queries failed to surface in the first place.\
Test C (pre-fetch value) \'97 include. After Strategy A, look at which sources came from the pre-phase aggregator searches vs the main 30 queries. If the pre-phase surfaced zero unique sources (as in Morocco), that's evidence it's not worth keeping for European cities.\
Test F (direct publication fetch) \'97 exclude from Strategy A observation. Test F requires actively choosing to go directly to publications rather than searching for them \'97 you can't observe this from a run that used the standard search approach. It needs its own dedicated run later and is Priority 3 anyway.\
\
Session gap: Same day, archive files manually between runs\
Since you don't want to wait a day, the manual archive approach is the right answer. It's perfectly adequate for ensuring independence \'97 the contamination risk from memory is minimal since each Claude Code session starts fresh. The real contamination risk is the shared files, which the archive step eliminates.\
