\fs32 \cf2 What Tests E and F would tell us\
Test E would test whether increasing Portuguese queries from 5 to 8-10 (reducing EN from 4) produces more both-pool entries. Based on the Lisbon result, this is worth examining \'97 Strategy A's 23 both-pool entries came heavily from multiple Time Out PT articles. The question is whether even more PT-focused searching would surface additional PT sources like Mesa Marcada (which Strategy B found but Strategy A missed).\
Test F would test whether directly fetching known publications (TimeOut Lisboa, Mesa Marcada, Observador) at the start of the pipeline \'97 before running any searches \'97 produces better results than letting searches discover them. This is motivated by the finding that Mesa Marcada (Miguel Pires) was missed by Strategy A entirely despite being a high-quality source.\
\
My honest assessment of whether to run Tests E and F\
Test E \'97 worth running before the Portugal batch. The Lisbon result showed that PT sources drove most of the both-pool count. If a rebalanced angle distribution (more PT, less EN) consistently finds sources like Mesa Marcada that Strategy A missed, that's a meaningful improvement. The test would take one additional Lisbon run \'97 about 30 minutes.\
Test F \'97 also worth running, and actually more actionable than Test E. The Mesa Marcada finding is a concrete gap in Strategy A. If we knew ahead of time which high-quality publications to fetch directly (Mesa Marcada for Lisbon, Observador, Vis\'e3o SE7E), we could produce a richer pack with fewer searches. The question is whether this generalises to new cities where we don't know the publications in advance.\
\
My recommendation\
Run Test F before the Portugal batch \'97 it directly addresses the Mesa Marcada gap and would take one more Lisbon run. Skip Test E for now \'97 the rebalancing question is less urgent and can be inferred partially from the Test F results.\
