\cf2 Good instinct to pause for a transparency review. Let me be honest about several things that deserve more scrutiny.\
\
1. The both-pool metric may be structurally biased toward Strategy A\
Strategy A found multiple Time Out PT articles (S2, S3, S4) \'97 three separate articles from the same publisher. This inflated the both-pool count because many restaurants appeared in multiple Time Out PT articles AND in Time Out EN. Effectively, Time Out's own internal coverage across different article formats was driving cross-confirmation rather than genuinely independent writers independently recommending the same places.\
This is a meaningful transparency concern. The LocalBite both-pool signal is designed to reflect independent editorial voices from different language communities agreeing. Three articles from the same publisher (Time Out PT) contributing to both-pool with one article from another publisher (Time Out EN) is a weaker signal than, say, Mesa Marcada (independent PT critic) and Culinary Backstreets (independent EN writer) independently naming the same place \'97 which is what Strategy B produced.\
The honest conclusion: Strategy A's 23 both-pool count is technically valid but editorially weaker than it appears. Strategy B's 8 both-pool entries from genuinely independent sources may actually be a higher-quality signal per entry, even if the count is lower. We declared Strategy A the winner based on quantity \'97 not quality of the both-pool signal.\
\
2. The concentration cap nearly fired on Strategy B but not Strategy A \'97 and we should examine why\
Ola Daniela reached 29.4% in Strategy B \'97 just under the 30% cap. In Strategy A, Time Out PT held S2, S3, and S4 \'97 three sources from the same publisher. If we applied the concentration cap at the publisher level rather than the article level, Time Out PT would have exceeded 30% in Strategy A too.\
We did not flag this in the findings. The concentration cap as currently designed operates at the source/article level, not the publisher level. This means a single publisher producing multiple articles can dominate the both-pool pool without triggering the cap. This is a structural gap in the pipeline rules worth documenting.\
\
3. Strategy B's sources are arguably better quality even if fewer\
Mesa Marcada / Miguel Pires is a dedicated independent Portuguese food critic writing specifically about restaurants. Observador is one of Portugal's most credible independent digital newspapers. Culinary Backstreets is a highly respected independent food writing platform. Ola Daniela is a documented Lisbon resident food blogger.\
By contrast, Strategy A's Time Out sources are editorial team content from a commercial listings platform that also operates the Time Out Market food hall in Lisbon \'97 a direct commercial conflict of interest with restaurant recommendations that we did not flag.\
This is a significant transparency gap. Time Out Market Lisboa is one of the most prominent food venues in Lisbon. Time Out Lisboa recommending restaurants while operating a competing food venue is a meaningful editorial conflict that the pipeline did not surface or flag.\
\
4. The test design had an imbalance we didn't acknowledge\
Strategy A found Time Out PT through Angles B and D (city-wide PT and neighbourhood PT queries). Strategy B reduced these angles to allocate more queries to writer-first searches. This means Strategy B was structurally less likely to find Time Out PT \'97 not because writer-first is inferior but because we reduced exactly the queries that surface aggregator-type publications.\
A cleaner test would have kept the PT city-wide and neighbourhood query counts identical between strategies and only varied the writer-first angle count. As designed, Strategy B changed two variables simultaneously (added pre-mapping, reduced standard angles) making it harder to isolate the cause of the difference.\
\
5. We don't know if the Lisbon result generalises\
Lisbon is a particularly well-documented city with multiple Time Out PT articles available in 2025-2026. Porto, Coimbra, Braga, and \'c9vora may not have the same density of Time Out PT coverage. If Strategy A's advantage came specifically from Lisbon's Time Out PT article density \'97 which may not exist in smaller Portuguese cities \'97 the test result may not generalise to the Portugal batch.\
\
Revised conclusions\
The findings document as written is accurate on the metrics but presents conclusions that are more definitive than the evidence warrants. A more honest summary would be:\
Strategy A produced more both-pool entries by count but the quality of those entries is questionable \'97 they relied heavily on multiple Time Out PT articles from a publisher with a commercial conflict of interest, and the independence standard for those articles meeting the both-pool criteria deserves further scrutiny.\
Strategy B produced fewer but arguably higher-quality both-pool entries from genuinely independent sources with no obvious commercial conflicts.\
The test design conflated two variables (pre-mapping and reduced standard angles) making it impossible to isolate which change drove the difference.\
The result may not generalise beyond Lisbon's specific Time Out PT article density.\
Recommended additions to the findings document:\
