\cf2 This is extremely revealing. Two separate issues caused Time Out's exclusion, and they compound each other in an important way.\
\
Issue 1 \'97 COI check misapplied\
The log confirms what I suspected \'97 the COI check correctly identified the Time Out Market conflict per the KNOWN_COMMERCIAL_CONFLICTS variable, but the pipeline then excluded Time Out rather than flagging and including it. The prompt said "disclose, do not reject" but the agent rejected anyway. This is a prompt compliance failure.\
Issue 2 \'97 Sibling edition check produced a different finding than Strategy A\
This is more significant and was not anticipated. The sibling check in Strategy A found EN and PT editions are independently produced (different authors, licensing model). The sibling check in Strategy C found they are NOT independently produced \'97 same publisher (Time Out Group).\
These two findings directly contradict each other across Strategy A and Strategy C. Both runs examined the same publication and reached opposite conclusions.\
Which finding is correct? The evidence from Strategy A's log was: different authors, different article dates, licensing model with editorial independence requirement. The evidence from Strategy C's log is: same publisher Time Out Group.\
Both are technically true. Time Out EN and PT have different editorial teams writing different articles \'97 but they share the same parent company. The question is which of these facts matters for the both-pool independence standard.\
\
This reveals a deeper conceptual problem\
The both-pool signal was designed to detect independent editorial agreement \'97 two writers from different language communities, without coordination, naming the same restaurant. Time Out EN and Time Out PT share a brand, a parent company, and potentially editorial direction even if the bylines differ. A restaurant that Time Out Group wants to promote could appear in both editions without genuine independent agreement.\
On the other hand, Time Out Lisboa's PT editorial team genuinely writes different articles from the EN team. Rita Chantre (S2) and Francisco Rom\'e3o Pereira (S1) are not the same person and do not appear to coordinate their recommendations. The overlap between their articles likely reflects genuine agreement about Lisbon's best restaurants, not coordinated promotion.\
\
The honest conclusion\
Strategy C's sibling check finding raises a legitimate question that Strategy A's sibling check dismissed too quickly. The right answer is probably somewhere between the two positions:\
