\fs32 \cf2 These are fundamentally different segments of Lisbon's restaurant scene. Independent EN writers (Culinary Backstreets, Ola Daniela) favour neighbourhood character restaurants. Independent PT critics (Mesa Marcada, Observador) favour high-concept and Michelin-adjacent restaurants. No restaurant appears in both pools.\
\
This reveals something profound about the both-pool signal\
Strategy A's 23 both-pool entries came almost entirely from Time Out EN + Time Out PT \'97 the same publisher writing about the same restaurants in two languages. That is not independent editorial agreement. It is one organisation's recommendations translated across language editions.\
Strategy C's 0 both-pool entries from genuinely independent sources reveals that independent EN and PT food critics in Lisbon do not overlap in their recommendations. They are writing for different audiences with different tastes \'97 EN expat/tourist-facing writers recommend casual neighbourhood spots; PT critics recommend fine dining and high-concept restaurants.\
The honest conclusion about the both-pool signal for Lisbon:\
The both-pool signal as designed rewards breadth of overlapping coverage. Time Out achieves this artificially by publishing in multiple languages about the same restaurants. Genuinely independent critics don't overlap \'97 not because one is wrong, but because they're writing for different audiences about different types of restaurants.\
This is a significant finding about the product itself, not just the test.\
\
