\fs32 \cf2 It uses OSM-based data like Nominatim, and one reviewer noted it is "API-compatible with Nominatim and just works." The storage terms appear permissive for the free tier. The main risk is the attribution requirement \'97 a link on the LocalBite site would be needed.\
Geoapify is also OSM-based, offers 3,000 free requests per day with permissive terms, and runs both Nominatim and Photon behind its API. It would likely perform similarly to running Nominatim + Photon directly but with a managed service layer. Less relevant for LocalBite since we're already running those two directly.\
Azure Maps can be ruled out \'97 similar restrictive storage terms to Google and HERE, and no advantage over other options.\
\
The honest summary for LocalBite's specific situation:\
For a hobby project geocoding 30-60 restaurants per city a few times a month, the distinction between commercial services is mostly about legal compliance and data quality rather than cost or volume. The key question is: which legally compliant service performs best for both European and Moroccan cities?\
