\fs32 \cf2 The honest summary for LocalBite:\
OpenCage is legally cleaner \'97 permanent storage explicitly permitted regardless of subscription status. But the free trial is for testing only, so ongoing use requires $50/month. For a hobby project that's a real cost.\
LocationIQ has a genuinely free commercial tier with attribution, 5,000 requests/day, and Nominatim-compatible API (minimal integration effort). The storage limitation on the free tier (48-hour cache) is a problem for permanently storing coordinates in GitHub \'97 but the "store response data forever" language on their pricing page suggests the coordinate values themselves can be kept, only the request-response caching has the 48-hour limit. This ambiguity needs clarifying directly with LocationIQ before using it.\
The practical recommendation for a hobby project:\
Use LocationIQ's free tier for geocoding, clarify their storage terms for the coordinate values specifically, and add the required attribution link to the LocalBite footer. If storage is confirmed permitted, LocationIQ is the best option \'97 free, Nominatim-compatible, double OpenCage's free request limit, commercial use permitted.\
If LocationIQ's storage terms prove ambiguous or restrictive, fall back to Nominatim + Photon (fully legal, no key, no attribution) and accept the higher manual lookup rate.\
