\fs32 \cf2 \
Why this applies to LocalBite specifically \'97 two separate violations:\
Violation 1 \'97 "building a repository of location assets"\
LocalBite stores coordinates in a JSON file in a public GitHub repository. That is precisely what HERE describes as "building a repository of location assets." The term "repository" is not accidental \'97 it is the exact word HERE uses, and it is the exact word GitHub uses to describe what LocalBite's project is.\
Violation 2 \'97 "scaling one request to serve multiple end users"\
The LocalBite viewer serves restaurant location data to every person who opens the site. Those coordinates were obtained from HERE via one geocoding request per restaurant, and are now being used to serve every viewer of the site. That is textbook "scaling one request to serve multiple end users."\
There is no "hobby project" exception in HERE's terms. The terms apply uniformly to all users of the developer portal regardless of whether the project is commercial or personal, large or small. The freemium plan gives you 1,000 free requests per day \'97 it does not give you different storage rights than a paid plan. The 30-day limit and the prohibition on multi-user serving apply equally to free and paid accounts on the developer portal.\
\
One nuance worth acknowledging honestly:\
HERE is a large commercial company that has never sued a hobby project developer for storing geocoordinates in a public JSON file. The practical risk of enforcement for a site with LocalBite's current traffic is essentially zero. Many developers use HERE coordinates in ways that technically violate these terms without consequence.\
But the question you asked was whether the data can be used \'97 and the honest answer is that the terms explicitly prohibit the specific combination of permanent storage + multi-user serving that LocalBite requires, regardless of project scale. Whether HERE would ever notice or care about a hobby project is a separate question from whether it is permitted.\
