\fs32 \cf2 What this means for LocalBite:\
OpenCage runs more geocoders and draws on more open data sources than LocationIQ. However \'97 and this is the honest caveat \'97 none of these additional sources are commercial POI databases. They are all open data sources: place name gazetteers, boundary datasets, address collections, and terrain data. None of them are equivalent to HERE's proprietary restaurant POI database.\
The practical implication remains the same as for LocationIQ: OpenCage's additional sources are unlikely to find restaurants that Nominatim + Photon miss. The main benefit of OpenCage over running Nominatim + Photon directly is managed infrastructure, a single API endpoint, and the aggregation of 10 geocoders returning the best result \'97 which may occasionally produce a better match through ensemble scoring even if the underlying data is similar.\
The key difference between OpenCage and LocationIQ for LocalBite is not data coverage but terms:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls478\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
OpenCage: permanent storage permitted, no attribution required, but free tier is testing-only \'97 ongoing use requires ~$50/month\
\ls478\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
LocationIQ: permanent storage permitted, attribution link required, free tier commercial use explicitly permitted at no cost\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 For a hobby project the LocationIQ free tier with an attribution link is the more practical choice. For a project that might grow or where clean terms without attribution obligations matter, OpenCage's paid tier is the cleaner option.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
