\fs32 \cf2 Searched the web\
\
Now I have enough to do a genuinely critical assessment. Here it is:\
\
Critical assessment of OpenCage's sources for European restaurant geocoding:\
OpenStreetMap \'97 the only source that truly matters for LocalBite The primary source for both services. OSM coverage in Western Europe (Portugal, Spain, France) is excellent and well-maintained. This is where Nominatim finds the 58% it already finds. No advantage to either service here \'97 they both use the same OSM data.\
Yahoo! GeoPlanet \'97 effectively dead The last GeoPlanet data release was June 2012, after which Yahoo discontinued the download. The API was dropped in 2015 and fully shut down in 2016.
\fs24 \cf4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GeoPlanet"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb27 Wikipedia\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf28 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 OpenCage states they use GeoPlanet's WOEID identifiers \'97 but the dataset hasn't been updated in over 13 years. For finding a restaurant opened in 2024 in Lisbon, this data is completely useless. It contributes nothing meaningful to European restaurant geocoding.\
Ordnance Survey OpenSpace \'97 discontinued and UK-only OS OpenSpace was taken offline in August 2021 and replaced with a new data hub.
\fs24 \cf4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pedalnorth.com/new-ordnance-survey-mapping/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \cb27 Pedal North\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf28 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Even when it was active it was UK-only and covered geographic features, not restaurant POIs. Zero value for Lisbon, Barcelona, or Marrakesh.\
Natural Earth Data \'97 boundaries not restaurants Natural Earth is a dataset of country boundaries, coastlines, populated places at city/town level, and physical features. It has no restaurant-level POI data. It helps OpenCage identify which country a coordinate is in \'97 useful for annotations \'97 but contributes nothing to finding a restaurant named "Broto" in Chiado.\
Thematic Mapping \'97 country-level boundaries A dataset of country borders and world population statistics. No relevance to restaurant geocoding whatsoever.\
Zillow \'97 US residential property data US-only. Zero relevance for any of LocalBite's current or planned cities.\
MaxMind \'97 IP geolocation Used for identifying a user's country from their IP address. Not relevant to forward geocoding by restaurant name.\
Flickr shapefiles \'97 neighbourhood boundary polygons These are crowd-sourced neighbourhood boundary shapes from geotagged Flickr photos. They help define neighbourhood boundaries but contain no restaurant names or coordinates.\
US Census Bureau / TIGER \'97 US addresses US-only. Zero relevance.\
GeoNames \'97 moderate relevance GeoNames is a global gazetteer of place names \'97 cities, towns, neighbourhoods, landmarks. It has some POI data but primarily covers administrative and geographic entities. It would help OpenCage find "Chiado" or "Alfama" as neighbourhoods but is unlikely to have individual restaurant entries. Moderate value for neighbourhood-level geocoding, minimal value for restaurant-name geocoding.\
Data Science Toolkit / Two Fishes \'97 legacy geocoders Both are older open-source geocoders that OpenCage runs as backend services. Two Fishes was developed by Foursquare and focuses on interpreting free-text location queries \'97 it excels at parsing "near the Eiffel Tower" type queries, not restaurant name lookups. Data Science Toolkit is a collection of open data tools, mostly US-focused. Neither adds meaningful restaurant discovery capability for Europe.\
G-NAF \'97 Australia only Irrelevant.\
\
Critical assessment of LocationIQ's sources for European restaurant geocoding:\
OpenStreetMap \'97 same as OpenCage Same primary source, same coverage, same value.\
GeoNames \'97 same as OpenCage Same dataset, same moderate value for place names, minimal for restaurants.\
OpenAddresses \'97 address-level data, relevant OpenAddresses aggregates government-released address datasets. In Europe this means official postal address registries from national governments \'97 France's Base Adresse Nationale, Portugal's CAOP, Spain's CartoCiudad. These are street-level address datasets, not POI databases. They would help find a restaurant's street address if the address is known, but since we're searching by name not address this provides limited additional benefit over OSM.\
Who's On First \'97 neighbourhood boundaries Mapbox's open gazetteer covers countries, regions, cities, and neighbourhoods with clean identifiers. Like Flickr shapefiles, it helps define geographic context but doesn't contain restaurant names.\
Quattroshapes \'97 administrative boundaries Foursquare's open boundary dataset. Similar to Who's On First \'97 geographic context, not restaurant POIs.\
TIGER / G-NAF \'97 US and Australia only Irrelevant for Europe and Morocco.\
\
The honest verdict for Europe:\
Neither OpenCage nor LocationIQ has sources that would meaningfully outperform Nominatim + Photon for finding restaurant names in European cities. The critical finding is this:\
Every additional source both services list \'97 GeoPlanet, Ordnance Survey, Natural Earth, Flickr shapefiles, Who's On First, Quattroshapes, OpenAddresses, GeoNames \'97 is either discontinued, geographic/administrative boundaries only, address-level not POI, or irrelevant to Europe. None of them are commercial restaurant POI databases.\
The only genuinely useful data for finding a restaurant named "Broto" in Chiado is OSM \'97 which Nominatim and Photon already access directly. OpenCage's 10 geocoders and LocationIQ's additional sources provide:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls479\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Better neighbourhood identification 
\f2 \uc0\u10003 
\f0  (minor benefit)\
\ls479\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Better address parsing 
\f2 \uc0\u10003 
\f0  (irrelevant \'97 we search by name not address)\
\ls479\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Better country/region disambiguation 
\f2 \uc0\u10003 
\f0  (largely handled by bounding box)\
\ls479\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Additional restaurant POI data 
\f6 \uc0\u10007 
\f0  (none \'97 all additional sources lack this)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The expected performance for both OpenCage and LocationIQ on Lisbon is therefore similar to Photon \'97 approximately 70-75% automated hit rate, not the 90%+ that HERE achieved through its proprietary restaurant POI database.\
The 20 percentage point gap that HERE provided for European cities came from its commercial restaurant database (sourced from TripAdvisor, business directories, and commercial POI aggregators). No open-data service can replicate this because that data is not open.\
\
Final recommendation:\
For European cities, the honest ranking is:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls480\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Nominatim + Photon \'97 free, no key, legally clean, ~70-75% hit rate\
\ls480\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
LocationIQ free tier \'97 same data, managed infrastructure, attribution required, ~70-75% hit rate \'97 marginal improvement over direct Photon in reliability only\
\ls480\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
OpenCage paid \'97 same data again, cleaner terms, $50/month, ~70-75% hit rate\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 None of these will recover HERE's lost 20 percentage points. That gap \'97 approximately 8-10 restaurants per European city \'97 will need manual Google Maps lookup regardless of which service is used.\
The decision is therefore not about data quality but about reliability vs cost vs legal cleanliness. For a hobby project at current scale, Nominatim + Photon is the right answer. When LocalBite grows to a point where Photon's uptime matters, LocationIQ free tier is the natural upgrade.\
