\fs32 \cf2 The critical question \'97 would Overpass find restaurants that Nominatim and Photon miss?\
This is the only question that matters for LocalBite, and the answer is: not in practice, no.\
Both Nominatim and Photon are geocoders built on top of the same OSM database that Overpass queries. If a restaurant is in OSM with a 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 name
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  tag, Nominatim will find it. If Nominatim misses it (which happens due to indexing strategy, address completeness, or query parsing), Photon \'97 which uses a different indexing approach optimised for fuzzy free-text search \'97 will often catch it.\
Overpass queries the raw OSM data directly, bypassing the geocoding layer entirely. In theory this means it could find nodes that Nominatim's indexing has deprioritised or excluded. In practice the gap is very small and cuts both ways \'97 Overpass would also surface false positives that Nominatim's ranking suppresses.\
There is one specific scenario where Overpass genuinely outperforms Nominatim and Photon: when a restaurant has no address data in OSM but has a name tag. Nominatim weights address completeness heavily \'97 a restaurant node with only 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 amenity=restaurant
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  and 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 name=Broto
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  and no street/postcode may rank very low or not appear at all. Overpass finds it regardless because it queries by tag, not by address index. For cities where OSM contributors have added restaurant names but not full addresses \'97 which is plausible for Marrakesh and Fes \'97 this could be a genuine advantage.\
\
The practical problem for LocalBite\
Overpass returns all restaurants matching a name filter in a bounding box, not the single best match. For a common name like "Caf\'e9 Lisboa" a query might return 15 results. Nominatim returns a ranked list; Overpass returns a flat set. LocalBite's geocoding script would need substantial additional logic to:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls488\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Filter by 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 amenity=restaurant
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  (or 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 amenity=cafe
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  etc.)\
\ls488\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Apply fuzzy name matching via regex (
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 name~"Broto",i
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 )\
\ls488\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Disambiguate multiple results by distance from city centre or by address completeness\
\ls488\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Handle way geometries (restaurants mapped as polygons rather than points) by computing centroids\
\ls488\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Score confidence without any built-in ranking signal\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 This is achievable but represents meaningfully more engineering than the current Nominatim + Photon stack, and the data reward is the same OSM dataset.\
\
Summary verdict\
Overpass is not a better geocoder than Nominatim + Photon for LocalBite's use case \'97 it is a different tool that happens to query the same underlying data. It is worth considering for one specific scenario: if testing reveals that Nominatim and Photon are missing restaurants in Marrakesh or Fes that are clearly visible in OSM (by checking Overpass Turbo manually), then a targeted Overpass fallback query for those cities could be added as a Combination 3 option. For European cities where OSM address data is dense, the gain would be negligible.\
It does not close the gap with HERE. That gap remains a data problem, not a query strategy problem.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
