\cf2 That's a smart reason to choose Toronto \'97 dogfooding the proximity feature on your home city will produce much better feedback than testing it on a city you don't know well.\
A few things worth thinking through before running Toronto:\
Toronto is a different editorial landscape to everything done so far\
All current cities have been in languages where the source pool is relatively contained \'97 EN/FR/AR for Morocco, EN/PT for Lisbon, EN/ES for Spain. Toronto's food writing is almost entirely English, which simplifies source discovery, but the city has an unusually dense and sophisticated restaurant criticism scene \'97 Toronto Life, The Globe and Mail, blogTO, Eater Toronto, NOW Magazine, local food bloggers. The both-pool signal will need rethinking since there is no meaningful second-language food writing pool for Toronto the way there is for Lisbon or Marrakesh.\
The both-pool definition doesn't translate well\
Both-pool was designed to capture editorial consensus across language communities. Toronto doesn't have a meaningful French or non-English food writing scene for local restaurants. You could redefine both-pool for Toronto as "recommended by two editorially independent English-language publications" \'97 which is a meaningful signal \'97 but it changes the definition in a way that makes cross-city comparison less clean. Worth deciding before running the prompt.\
Price currency and levels\
Currently set up for EUR and MAD. Toronto needs CAD with appropriate levels \'97 probably something like: $ under 30pp, $ 30\'9660pp, $ $ 60\'96100pp, $ $$ over $100pp.\
The prompt needs new city variables throughout\
Geographic boundary, neighbourhood list, source examples, price levels, currency \'97 all need Toronto-specific values in Part 1.\
On the proximity feature itself\
Before running Toronto it would be worth sketching what the proximity feature actually needs from the data. If it's "show me restaurants within X km of my location" the current JSON structure already supports it \'97 lat/lng are present and the viewer has Leaflet. The feature would be a filter or map behaviour change, not a data change. If it's something more like "I'm at King and Spadina, what's nearby" that's the same thing but with a user location input. Either way Toronto's data requirements are the same as any other city.\
Geocoding will be excellent\
Toronto OSM coverage is dense and well-maintained. Nominatim hit rate for Toronto restaurants will be significantly higher than Lisbon \'97 expect 75\'9685% automated coverage, minimal manual lookups.\
Do you want to sketch the Toronto prompt variables now, or think through the both-pool question first?\
