THE BOTH-POOL QUESTION\
This is the most important decision for Toronto. Three options:\
Option A \'97 Drop both-pool entirely for Toronto Toronto is a single-language food writing city. The both-pool signal was designed for cities where two distinct editorial communities write in different languages. Forcing it onto Toronto produces a weaker signal (two English publications agreeing) that means something different from a Lisbon both-pool entry. Display all Toronto restaurants without the both-pool badge. Honest and clean.\
Option B \'97 Redefine both-pool as "two independent English publications" Multi-source endorsement is still a meaningful quality signal even in a single language. A restaurant recommended by both Toronto Life and Eater Toronto is more confidently recommended than one appearing in only one source. The badge label would need to change from "Two languages" to something like "Multiple sources" or "Editors agree." This changes the cross-city meaning of the badge.\
Option C \'97 Use a neighbourhood diversity signal instead Toronto's food writing has clear critical communities \'97 the legacy press (Globe, Post, Toronto Life) and the digital-native press (Eater, blogTO, NOW). A restaurant endorsed by both communities could be flagged. Interesting but complex to implement.\
My recommendation is Option B with a label change \'97 "Multiple sources" is honest, meaningful, and useful to a viewer using the site. It is a weaker signal than a true cross-language both-pool but it is not meaningless. The alternative is having no quality signal at all for Toronto which makes the city pack feel less curated.\
