The both-pool recommendation\
My recommendation is Option B \'97 redefine as "two independent sources" but with one specific refinement: distinguish between the legacy press tier (Toronto Life, Globe, Star, NOW) and the digital/independent tier (Foodism, Eater, Madame Marie, Toronto Food Blog). A restaurant endorsed by one from each tier is a more meaningful signal than two from the same tier.\
The badge label changes from "Two languages" to "Multiple sources" in the viewer for Toronto specifically, or more elegantly, the viewer could show a simple source count badge ("2 sources", "3 sources") rather than the language-pool concept entirely for English-only cities. That would also be more honest to the viewer about what the signal means.\
The practical argument for keeping it: Toronto Life alone recommends 30\'9640 restaurants per year. Foodism recommends 23. The overlap \'97 restaurants that appear in both independent editorial lists \'97 is a genuinely useful quality filter for a viewer who wants to know which restaurants the critical community broadly agrees on, not just which one publication likes. That is exactly what LocalBite is trying to surface.\
The practical argument against: it muddies the cross-city meaning of the badge. A Lisbon "both-pool" entry (Portuguese critic + English critic independently agreeing) is a stronger signal than a Toronto "multi-source" entry (Toronto Life + Foodism agreeing), and displaying them with the same visual treatment implies equivalence that isn't quite there.\
My actual recommendation: Use Option B with the source count display, but document clearly in the viewer's "About" or tooltip that the signal means something slightly different for Toronto. The integrity is maintained as long as you're transparent about it. The alternative \'97 no quality signal at all for Toronto \'97 makes the city pack feel less curated than every other city in the portfolio, which is the wrong direction as LocalBite grows.\
