\cf2 Good time to think this through properly. Let me lay out what the proximity feature actually is, what it needs, and the design options.\
\
What "proximity" means in practice for LocalBite\
There are two distinct use cases that sound similar but are different:\
Use case A \'97 Passive proximity: "Show me what's near me right now." User opens LocalBite on their phone while standing somewhere in Toronto. The app detects their location and surfaces nearby restaurants from the pack.\
Use case B \'97 Active proximity: "I'm going to be at King and Spadina on Saturday \'97 what's good nearby?" User is planning ahead, not physically present. They input a location manually and get results around it.\
Both are useful. Use case A is the dogfooding scenario you described \'97 using LocalBite on your home city while actually out in Toronto. Use case B is the travel planning scenario \'97 using it before a trip to Lisbon or Marrakesh to identify restaurants near where you're staying.\
\
What the feature needs from the data\
Nothing new. Every city pack already has lat/lng for all restaurants. The haversine formula (distance between two coordinates) is trivial to implement in JavaScript. No API calls, no external service, no data changes.\
\
Design options \'97 from simple to complex:\
Option 1 \'97 Radius filter on the map\
The simplest implementation. Add a "Near me" button to the map view. On click, it requests the user's GPS location via the browser's 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf7 \cb8 navigator.geolocation
\fs32 \cf2 \cb1  API, then filters the visible pins to only those within a chosen radius (1km, 2km, 5km). A slider or set of preset buttons controls the radius.\
Pros: very simple to build, works on mobile immediately, no address input needed, integrates cleanly with existing Leaflet map.\
Cons: only works for Use case A (physically present), no use for trip planning.\
Option 2 \'97 Location search input\
Add a text field: "Search from a location" or "I'm near...". User types a street address or intersection ("King and Spadina", "Chinatown", "my hotel on Bloor"). The input is geocoded \'97 converted to coordinates \'97 and then the radius filter runs from that point instead of the user's GPS.\
This requires a geocoding call for the typed address. Free options: Nominatim (no API key, rate limited, fine for user-triggered single lookups), or Photon. The geocoded point drops a marker on the map showing "searching from here" and restaurants within radius are highlighted.\
Pros: covers both use cases, works for trip planning from anywhere in the world, works on desktop.\
Cons: requires geocoding the typed address, adds a dependency, slightly more complex to build.\
Option 3 \'97 Tap-to-set-origin on the map\
User taps or clicks anywhere on the map to set their search origin point. A circle radiates out from that point showing the search radius. Restaurants within the circle are highlighted, others dimmed.\
Pros: intuitive for mobile, no typing required, no geocoding dependency, works for trip planning ("I know my hotel is roughly here").\
Cons: requires knowing the city geography well enough to tap in the right area \'97 less useful for unfamiliar cities.\
Option 4 \'97 Combination\
"Near me" button for GPS detection + tap-to-set-origin as fallback + optional address search. This is the full-featured version.\
\
My recommendation\
Start with Option 1 for Toronto \'97 it's the dogfooding case and takes an afternoon to build. A "Near me" button on the map that filters to pins within a 1km/2km/5km radius using GPS. This gives you something real to test immediately.\
Add Option 3 (tap-to-set-origin) as a second step \'97 it extends the feature to trip planning without needing address geocoding. The interaction is: tap anywhere on the map 
\f2 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  circle appears 
\f2 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  restaurants within circle are highlighted.\
Save Option 2 (address search input) for later when you have feedback from real use. It's the most powerful but also the most work and introduces a dependency.\
One important UX consideration: proximity filtering should work alongside the existing filters (price, cuisine), not replace them. "Show me level 2 price restaurants within 1km of me" is a much more useful query than either filter alone. The implementation should stack the proximity radius on top of whatever filters are already active.\
\
One data gap to flag\
Toronto will have good coordinate coverage from Nominatim \'97 probably 80%+ automated. But restaurants without coordinates (those that need manual lookup after the pipeline runs) will be invisible to the proximity filter entirely. They'll show in list view but won't appear on the map at all, which means they're excluded from proximity results. This is honest \'97 you can only show proximity for restaurants you can locate \'97 but worth being aware of when you evaluate the Toronto pack after the pipeline finishes.\
What's your instinct on which use case matters most to you as the initial test \'97 physically walking around Toronto, or planning where to eat before heading out?\
