GPS-only (Option 1) fails the proxy test\
If you build "Near me" using GPS and test it walking around Toronto, you learn nothing about whether the feature works for someone planning a trip to Lisbon from their couch in Toronto. That's the primary use case for every city except Toronto. So Option 1 alone is not a valid proxy.\
\
What passes the proxy test\
The feature needs to work in two modes that together cover all cities and both use cases:\
Mode A \'97 GPS (physically present) Tap "Near me", device locates you, radius filter activates. Works for Toronto dogfooding and for any future city a user is actually visiting.\
Mode B \'97 Tap-to-set-origin (planning ahead) Tap anywhere on the map to drop an origin point. Radius filter activates from that point. Works for trip planning to any city regardless of language, regardless of whether the user is physically there.\
Together these two modes cover every scenario without any address geocoding dependency, without any language assumptions, and without any city-specific logic. The same code works identically for Toronto, Lisbon, Marrakesh, and every future city.\
\
What the Toronto test actually validates\
If you build both modes and test in Toronto, you're validating:\
